export default {"14.6":{"problem_text":"A 45-ton boxcar A is moving in a railroad switchyard with a velocity of 5.6 mi/h toward cars B and C, which are both at rest with their brakes off at a short distance from each other. Car B is a 25-ton flatcar supporting a 30-ton container, and car C is a 40-ton boxcar. As the cars hit each other, they get automatically and tightly coupled. Determine the velocity of car A immediately after each of the two couplings, assuming that the container (a) does not slide on the flatcar, (b) slides after the first coupling but hits a stop before the second coupling occurs, (c) slides and hits the stop only after the second coupling has occurred.","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["Conservation of momentum is used, with mass in tons and velocity in mi/h.","Part (a): Assume the container does not slide on the flatcar. Calculate the velocity after the first coupling (v1) and after the second coupling (v2).","For the first coupling (A and B with container): (45)(5.6) = (45 + 25 + 30)v1; 252 = 100v1.","For the second coupling (A+B+container and C): (100)v1 = (100 + 40)v2; 100v1 = 140v2.","Part (b): Assume the container slides after the first coupling but stops before the second. Calculate the velocity after the first coupling (v1) and after the second coupling (v2).","For the first coupling (A and B): (45)(5.6) = (45 + 25)v1; 252 = 70v1. The container (30 tons) is assumed to be at rest relative to the ground.","For the second coupling (A+B and C): (70)v1 = (70 + 40)v2; 70v1 = 140v2. The container (30 tons) is still assumed at rest.","Part (c): Assume the container slides and stops only after the second coupling has occurred. Calculate the velocity after the first coupling (v1) and after the second coupling (v2).","For the first coupling (A and B): (45)(5.6) = (45 + 25)v1; 252 = 70v1. The container (30 tons) is assumed to be at rest.","For the second coupling (A+B and C with container): (70)v1 = (70 + 40)v2; 70v1 = 110v2. The container (30 tons) is now part of the coupled system for the second coupling."],"final_answer":"(a) v1 = 2.52 mi/h, v2 = 1.800 mi/h; (b) v1 = 3.60 mi/h, v2 = 1.800 mi/h; (c) v1 = 3.60 mi/h, v2 = 2.29 mi/h","page_num":802},"14.10":{"problem_text":"For the system of particles of Problem 14.9, determine (a) the position vector r of the mass center G of the system, (b) the linear momentum mv of the system, (c) the angular momentum H_G of the system about G. Also verify that the answers to this problem and to Problem 14.9 satisfy the equation given in Problem 14.27.\n\nPROBLEM 14.9 A system consists of three particles A, B, and C. We know that m_A = 3 kg, m_B = 4 kg, and m_C = 5 kg and that the velocities of the particles expressed in m/s are, respectively, v_A = -4i + 4j + 6k, v_B = -6i + 8j + 4k, and v_C = 2i - 6j - 4k. Determine the angular momentum H_O of the system about O.","method":"otro","steps":["Position vectors, (meters): r_A = 1.2i + 1.5k, r_B = 0.9i + 1.2j + 1.2k, r_C = 2.4j + 1.8k","Mass center (a): (m_A + m_B + m_C) * r = m_A * r_A + m_B * r_B + m_C * r_C","Substitute given values: 12r = (3)(1.2i + 1.5k) + (4)(0.9i + 1.2j + 1.2k) + (5)(2.4j + 1.8k)","Calculate r: r = 0.6i + 1.4j + 1.525k","Final result for r: r = (0.600 m)i + (1.400 m)j + (1.525 m)k","Linear momentum of each particle (kg * m/s):","For A: m_A * v_A = 3 * (-4i + 4j + 6k) = -12i + 12j + 18k","For B: m_B * v_B = 4 * (-6i + 8j + 4k) = -24i + 32j + 16k","For C: m_C * v_C = 5 * (2i - 6j - 4k) = 10i - 30j - 20k","Linear momentum of the system (b): mv = m_A * v_A + m_B * v_B + m_C * v_C","Substitute and sum: mv = (-12 - 24 + 10)i + (12 + 32 - 30)j + (18 + 16 - 20)k = -26i + 14j + 14k","Final result for mv: mv = -(26.0 kg * m/s)i + (14.00 kg * m/s)j + (14.00 kg * m/s)k","Position vectors relative to the mass center (meters):","r'_A = r_A - r = (1.2i + 1.5k) - (0.6i + 1.4j + 1.525k) = 0.6i - 1.4j - 0.025k","r'_B = r_B - r = (0.9i + 1.2j + 1.2k) - (0.6i + 1.4j + 1.525k) = 0.3i - 0.2j - 0.325k","r'_C = r_C - r = (2.4j + 1.8k) - (0.6i + 1.4j + 1.525k) = -0.6i + 1.0j + 0.275k"],"final_answer":"(a) r = (0.600 m)i + (1.400 m)j + (1.525 m)k, (b) mv = -(26.0 kg·m/s)i + (14.00 kg·m/s)j + (14.00 kg·m/s)k","page_num":809},"14.11":{"problem_text":"A system consists of three particles A, B, and C. We know that mA=3 kg, mB = 4 kg, and mc = 5 kg and that the velocities of the particles expressed in m/s are, respectively, vA = -4i+4j+6k, vB = vxi+vyj+4k, and vC = 2i-6j-4k. Determine (a) the components vx and vy of the velocity of particle B for which the angular momentum HO of the system about O is parallel to the z axis, (b) the corresponding value of HO.","method":"otro","steps":["Calculate the angular momentum HO of the system about O using the formula HO = rA x mAVA + rB x mBVB + rC x mCVC.","Express the position vectors rA, rB, and rC based on the given dimensions from the image.","Substitute the given masses and velocities into the angular momentum equation.","Perform the cross products and combine the terms to get the components of HO in the i, j, and k directions.","For HO to be parallel to the z-axis, the i and j components of HO must be zero: (7.2 - 4.8vy) = 0 and (-36 + 4.8vx) = 0.","Solve the equations from the previous step to find the values of vx and vy.","Substitute the found values of vx and vy back into the k-component of HO to find the corresponding value of HO."],"final_answer":"vx = 7.50 m/s, vy = 1.500 m/s, HO = -(40.2 kg·m²/s)k","page_num":811},"14.16":{"problem_text":"A 30-lb projectile is passing through the origin O with a velocity v₀ = (120 ft/s)i when it explodes into two fragments A and B, of weight 12 lb and 18 lb, respectively. Knowing that 3 s later the position of fragment A is (300 ft, 24 ft, -48 ft), determine the position of fragment B at the same instant. Assume a_y = -g = -32.2 ft/s² and neglect air resistance.","method":"f-ma","steps":["Determine the position of the mass center (r_bar) at t=3s, assuming the projectile had not exploded, using the equation of motion: r_bar = v₀t + (1/2)gt²j.","Substitute the given values into the equation: r_bar = (120 ft/s)(3 s)i - (1/2)(32.2 ft/s²)(3 s)²j.","Calculate the components of r_bar: r_bar = (360 ft)i - (144.9 ft)j.","Apply the principle of conservation of mass center: (m_A + m_B)r_bar = m_A r_A + m_B r_B. Note: the weights are given, so use W/g for masses.","Substitute the known values for the total mass, the masses of fragments A and B, and the position of fragment A (r_A = 300i + 24j - 48k).","Rearrange the equation to solve for r_B: 18r_B = (30/g)(360i - 144.9j) - (12/g)(300i + 24j - 48k).","Multiply by g to simplify and combine terms for i, j, and k components: 18r_B = (30 * 360 - 12 * 300)i + (-30 * 144.9 - 12 * 24)j + (12 * 48)k.","Calculate the numerical values: 18r_B = 7200i - 4635j + 576k.","Divide by 18 to find r_B."],"final_answer":"r_B = (400 ft)i - (258 ft)j + (32.0 ft)k","page_num":816},"14.18":{"problem_text":"In Problem 14.17, knowing that the wreckage of the small airplane was found at Point A (1200 m, 80 m) and the 1000-kg fragment of the helicopter at Point H1 (400 m, -200 m), and assuming that all pieces hit the ground at the same time, determine the coordinates of the Point H2 where the other fragment of the helicopter will be found.","method":"otro","steps":["At collision, the velocity of the helicopter (VH) is calculated using the given displacement (8400 m) over time (4(60 s)): VH = (8400 m)/(4(60 s)) i = (35.00 m/s)i.","The velocity of the airplane (VA) is calculated using its given displacement (16,000 m i - 12,000 m j) over time (4(60 s)): VA = (16,000 m i - 12,000 m j)/(4(60 s)) = (66.67 m/s)i - (50 m/s)j.","The velocity of the mass center (V_bar) is determined using the conservation of momentum (m_H + m_A)V_bar = m_H V_H + m_A V_A. Given the masses, 4500 V_bar = 3000(35.00i) + 1500(66.67i - 50j), which simplifies to V_bar = (45.556 m/s)i - (16.667 m/s)j.","For the vertical motion of the mass center, the time (t) to impact the ground from a height (h) of 1200 m is calculated using t = sqrt(2h/g) = sqrt(2(1200 m)/(9.81 m/s^2)) = 15.641 s.","The position of the mass center (r_bar) at the time of ground impact is found by r_bar = V_bar * t = (45.556i - 16.667j)(15.641) = (712.55 m)i - (260.69 m)j.","Using Eq. (14.12), the relationship between the mass center and the positions of the fragments is (m_H + m_A)r_bar = m_H1 r_H1 + m_H2 r_H2 + m_A r_A.","Substituting the known values: 4500(712.55i - 260.69j) = 1000(400i - 200j) + 2000r_H2 + 1500(1200i + 80j).","Rearranging the equation to solve for 2r_H2: 2r_H2 = (4.5 × 712.55 - 400 - 1.5 × 1200)i + (-4.5 × 260.69 + 200 - 1.5 × 80)j.","Calculating the components of 2r_H2 leads to the final position of r_H2."],"final_answer":"r_H2 = (503 m)i - (547 m)j","page_num":818},"14.19":{"problem_text":"Car A was traveling east at high speed when it collided at Point O with car B, which was traveling north at 72 km/h. Car C, which was traveling west at 90 km/h, was 10 m east and 3 m north of Point O at the time of the collision. Because the pavement was wet, the driver of car C could not prevent his car from sliding into the other two cars, and the three cars, stuck together, kept sliding until they hit the utility pole P. Knowing that the masses of cars A, B, and C are, respectively, 1500 kg, 1300 kg, and 1200 kg, and neglecting the forces exerted on the cars by the wet pavement, solve the problems indicated. Knowing that the coordinates of the utility pole are x_P = 18 m and y_P= 13.9 m, determine (a) the time elapsed from the first collision to the stop at P, (b) the speed of car A.","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["Let t be the time elapsed since the first collision. No external forces in the xy plane act on the system consisting of cars A, B, and C during the impacts with one another. The mass center of the system moves at the velocity it had before the collision.","Calculate the initial position of the mass center (X₀, Y₀). Given x_C = 10 m, y_C = 3 m, and assuming the problem text implies these are coordinates relative to O, it is stated that X₀ = 0.3x_C = (0.3)(10) = 3 m and Y₀ = 0.3y_C = (0.3)(3) = 0.9 m.","List the given velocities: v_A = v_A î, v_B = (20 m/s) ĵ, v_C = -(25 m/s) î. Note conversions for v_B and v_C from km/h to m/s: 72 km/h = 20 m/s, 90 km/h = 25 m/s.","Calculate the velocity of the mass center using the principle of conservation of momentum for the system (A + B + C). (m_A + m_B + m_C)V̄ = m_A v_A + m_B v_B + m_C v_C. The result is V̄ = 0.375v_A + 0.325v_B + 0.3v_C.","The collided cars hit the pole at r_P = x_P î + y_P ĵ. The position of the mass center at the time of impact with the pole is also given by r_P = X₀ î + Y₀ ĵ + V̄ t. Resolve this equation into x and y components.","x-component: x_P = X₀ + 0.375v_A t_P - 0.3v_C t_P (Equation 1)","y-component: y_P = Y₀ + 0.325v_B t_P (Equation 2)"],"final_answer":"","page_num":819},"14.20":{"problem_text":"Data:\nv_A = 129.6 km/h = 36 m/s, t_P = 2.4 s\nFrom (1), x_P = 3 + (0.375)(36)(2.4) - (0.3)(25)(2.4) = 17.4 m\nFrom (2), y_P = 0.9 + (0.325)(20)(2.4) = 16.5 m","method":"otro","steps":["Identify the given data: initial velocity v_A = 129.6 km/h, which is converted to 36 m/s; and time t_P = 2.4 s.","Calculate the x-coordinate (x_P) using the provided formula: x_P = 3 + (0.375)(36)(2.4) - (0.3)(25)(2.4).","Perform the multiplication and subtraction for the x-coordinate: x_P = 3 + 32.4 - 18 = 17.4 m.","Calculate the y-coordinate (y_P) using the provided formula: y_P = 0.9 + (0.325)(20)(2.4).","Perform the multiplication and addition for the y-coordinate: y_P = 0.9 + 15.6 = 16.5 m."],"final_answer":"x_P = 17.40 m, y_P = 16.50 m","page_num":822},"14.21":{"problem_text":"In a game of pool, ball A is moving with a velocity v₀ when it strikes balls B and C, which are at rest and aligned as shown. Knowing that after the collision the three balls move in the directions indicated, and that v₀ = 12 ft/s and v_C = 6.29 ft/s, determine the magnitude of the velocity of (a) ball A, (b) ball B.","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["Apply the conservation of linear momentum in the x direction:","m(12 ft/s) cos 45° = mv_A sin 4.3° + mv_B sin 37.4° + m(6.29 ft/s) cos 30°","Simplify the equation to: 0.07498v_A + 0.60738v_B = 3.0380 (1)","Apply the conservation of linear momentum in the y direction:","m(12 ft/s) sin 45° = mv_A cos 4.3° - mv_B cos 37.4° + m(6.29 ft/s) sin 30°","Simplify the equation to: 0.99719v_A - 0.79441v_B = 5.3403 (2)","To solve for v_A, multiply equation (1) by 0.79441 and equation (2) by 0.60738, then add the resulting equations:","0.66524v_A = 5.6570","Calculate v_A = 8.50 ft/s","To solve for v_B, multiply equation (1) by 0.99719 and equation (2) by -0.07498, then add the resulting equations:","0.66524v_B = 2.6290","Calculate v_B = 3.95 ft/s"],"final_answer":"v_A = 8.50 ft/s, v_B = 3.95 ft/s","page_num":823},"14.22":{"problem_text":"In a game of pool, ball A is moving with a velocity v₀ when it strikes balls B and C, which are at rest and aligned as shown. Knowing that after the collision the three balls move in the directions indicated and that v₀ = 12 ft/s and v_C = 6.29 ft/s, determine the magnitude of the velocity of (a) ball A, (b) ball B.","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["Conservation of linear momentum in the x direction is given by: m(12 ft/s)cos 30° = mv_A sin 7.4° + mv_B sin 49.3° + m(6.29)cos 45°. This simplifies to 0.12880v_A + 0.75813v_B = 5.9446 (Equation 1).","Conservation of linear momentum in the y direction is given by: m(12 ft/s)sin 30° = mv_A cos 7.4° - mv_B cos 49.3° + m(6.29)sin 45°. This simplifies to 0.99167v_A - 0.65210v_B = 1.5523 (Equation 2).","To find v_A, multiply Equation (1) by 0.65210, Equation (2) by 0.75813, and add the resulting equations: (0.65210)(0.12880v_A) + (0.65210)(0.75813v_B) = (0.65210)(5.9446)  and (0.75813)(0.99167v_A) - (0.75813)(0.65210v_B) = (0.75813)(1.5523). Adding these results in 0.83581v_A = 5.0533.","To find v_B, multiply Equation (1) by 0.99167, Equation (2) by -0.12880, and add the resulting equations: (0.99167)(0.12880v_A) + (0.99167)(0.75813v_B) = (0.99167)(5.9446) and (-0.12880)(0.99167v_A) - (-0.12880)(0.65210v_B) = (-0.12880)(1.5523). Adding these results in 0.83581v_B = 5.6951."],"final_answer":"(a) v_A = 6.05 ft/s, (b) v_B = 6.81 ft/s","page_num":824},"14.23":{"problem_text":"An expert archer demonstrates his ability by hitting tennis balls thrown by an assistant. A 58-g tennis ball has a velocity of (10 m/s)i - (2 m/s)j and is 10 m above the ground when it is hit by a 40-g arrow traveling with a velocity of (50 m/s)j + (70 m/s)k where j is directed upwards. Determine the position P where the ball and arrow will hit the ground relative to Point O located directly under the point of impact.","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["Assume that the ball and arrow move together after the hit.","Apply the conservation of momentum for the ball and arrow during the hit: m_A V_A + m_B V_B = (m_A + m_B)bar{V}.","Substitute the given values: (0.040 kg)(50j + 70k) m/s + (0.058 kg)(10i - 2j) m/s = (0.040 kg + 0.058 kg)bar{V}.","Calculate bar{V} = (5.9184 m/s)i + (19.2245 m/s)j + (28.5714 m/s)k.","After the hit, the ball and arrow move as a projectile. Analyze vertical motion first.","Use the vertical motion equation: y = y_0 + (v_y)_0 t - (1/2)gt^2.","Substitute initial conditions: y = 10 + 19.2245t - (1/2)(9.8)t^2.","Set y = 0 for when it hits the ground: -4.9t^2 + 19.2245t + 10 = 0.","Solve the quadratic equation for t. After rejecting the negative root, t = 4.3884 s.","Analyze horizontal motion using the equations: x = x_0 + (v_x)_0t and z = z_0 + (v_z)_0t.","Substitute values for x-component: x = 0 + (5.9184 m/s)(4.3884 s) = 26.0 m.","Substitute values for z-component: z = 0 + (28.5714 m/s)(4.3884 s) = 125.4 m."],"final_answer":"r_p = (26.0 m)i + (125.4 m)k","page_num":825},"14.25":{"problem_text":"PROBLEM 14.25 (Continued)","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["Conservation of momentum: mv₀ = mₐvₐ + mᵦvᵦ + m꜀v꜀","Substitute given values into the momentum equation:","Multiply by g and resolve into components to obtain three equations:","x-component: 480 = -37.5(vₐ/19.5) + 72(vᵦ/27)","y-component: -360 = 36(vᵦ/27) - 40.5(v꜀/22.5)","z-component: -14,400 = -90(vₐ/19.5) - 72(vᵦ/27) - 54(v꜀/22.5)","Solve the system of equations. From the x-component equation, solve for vₐ/19.5:","vₐ/19.5 = 86.033","From the y-component equation, solve for vᵦ/27:","vᵦ/27 = 51.475","From the z-component equation and substituting the values of vₐ/19.5 and vᵦ/27, solve for v꜀/22.5:","v꜀/22.5 = 54.644","Calculate the final velocities:","v_A = 86.033 * 19.5","v_B = 51.475 * 27","v_C = 54.644 * 22.5"],"final_answer":"vₐ = 1678 ft/s, vᵦ = 1390 ft/s, v꜀ = 1229 ft/s","page_num":829},"14.26":{"problem_text":"An 12-lb shell moving with a velocity v₀ = (40 ft/s)i - (30 ft/s)j - (1200 ft/s)k explodes at Point D into three fragments A, B, and C weighing, respectively, 4 lb, 3 lb, and 5 lb. Knowing that the fragments hit the vertical wall at the points indicated, determine the speed of each fragment immediately after the explosion.","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["Identify the initial position vector of the shell before explosion, r_D = 18k ft.","Identify the coordinates of the impact points of the fragments: A, B, and C. From the image, the coordinates appear to be: A corresponding to r_A = -7.5i ft, B corresponding to r_B = 18i + 9j ft, and C corresponding to r_C = -13.5j ft.","Calculate the relative position vectors from the explosion point D to each impact point: r_A/D = r_A - r_D = -7.5i - 18k ft, r_B/D = r_B - r_D = 18i + 9j - 18k ft, r_C/D = r_C - r_D = -13.5j - 18k ft.","Calculate the magnitudes of these relative position vectors: |r_A/D| = sqrt((-7.5)^2 + (-18)^2) = 19.5 ft, |r_B/D| = sqrt((18)^2 + (9)^2 + (-18)^2) = 27 ft, |r_C/D| = sqrt((-13.5)^2 + (-18)^2) = 22.5 ft.","Determine the unit vectors in the direction of the relative position vectors (which also represent the direction of the velocity vectors after the explosion, assuming gravity is neglected): λ_A = r_A/D / |r_A/D| = (1/19.5)(-7.5i - 18k), λ_B = r_B/D / |r_B/D| = (1/27)(18i + 9j - 18k), λ_C = r_C/D / |r_C/D| = (1/22.5)(-13.5j - 18k).","Express the velocity vectors of the fragments immediately after the explosion as v_A = v_A * λ_A, v_B = v_B * λ_B, v_C = v_C * λ_C, where v_A, v_B, v_C are the speeds of the fragments.","Apply the principle of conservation of momentum. The total momentum before the explosion must equal the total momentum after the explosion. Initial momentum P_initial = m_total * v₀. Final momentum P_final = m_A * v_A + m_B * v_B + m_C * v_C.","Masses of fragments: m_A = 4 lb, m_B = 3 lb, m_C = 5 lb. Total mass m_total = 4 + 3 + 5 = 12 lb.","Substitute the expressions for velocities and solve the resulting system of equations to find the speeds v_A, v_B, and v_C. (Note: The provided solution only sets up the initial vectors and unit vectors, the calculation for the speeds is not shown in the image.)","The magnitudes of r_A/D, r_B/D, and r_C/D are correctly calculated.","The unit vectors λ_A, λ_B, and λ_C are correctly derived."],"final_answer":"","page_num":null},"14.27":{"problem_text":"Derive the relation\n\nHₒ = r̅ × m v̅ + H_G\n\nbetween the angular momenta Hₒ and H_G defined in Eqs. (14.7) and (14.24), respectively. The vectors r̅ and v̅ define, respectively, the position and velocity of the mass center G of the system of particles relative to the newtonian frame of reference Oxyz, and m represents the total mass of the system.","method":"otro","steps":["From Eq. (14.7), we have the definition of the angular momentum about point O:","Hₒ = Σᵢ<binary data, 1 bytes>₁ⁿ (rᵢ × mᵢvᵢ)","We can express the position vector rᵢ in terms of the position vector of the mass center r̅ and the position vector of the particle relative to the mass center rᵢ':","rᵢ = r̅ + rᵢ'","Substitute this into the expression for Hₒ:","Hₒ = Σᵢ<binary data, 1 bytes>₁ⁿ [(r̅ + rᵢ') × mᵢvᵢ]","Expand the cross product using the distributive property:","Hₒ = Σᵢ<binary data, 1 bytes>₁ⁿ (r̅ × mᵢvᵢ + rᵢ' × mᵢvᵢ)","Separate the summation:","Hₒ = r̅ × Σᵢ<binary data, 1 bytes>₁ⁿ (mᵢvᵢ) + Σᵢ<binary data, 1 bytes>₁ⁿ (rᵢ' × mᵢvᵢ)","Recognize that Σᵢ<binary data, 1 bytes>₁ⁿ (mᵢvᵢ) is the total linear momentum of the system, which can be written as m v̅, where m is the total mass and v̅ is the velocity of the mass center.","Recognize that Σᵢ<binary data, 1 bytes>₁ⁿ (rᵢ' × mᵢvᵢ) is the angular momentum about the mass center G, H_G.","Substitute these back into the equation:","Hₒ = r̅ × m v̅ + H_G"],"final_answer":"Hₒ = r̅ × m v̅ + H_G","page_num":832},"14.28":{"problem_text":"Show that Eq. (14.23) may be derived directly from Eq. (14.11) by substituting for H_O the expression given in Problem 14.27.","method":"otro","steps":["From Eq. (14.7), H_O = sum_{i=1 to n} (r_i x m_i v_i)","= sum_{i=1 to n} [(r_bar + r'_i) x m_i v_i]","= r_bar x sum_{i=1 to n} (m_i v_i) + sum_{i=1 to n} (r'_i x m_i v_i)","= r_bar x m v_bar + H_G","Differentiating, H_dot_O = r_dot_bar x m v_bar + r_bar x m v_dot_bar + H_dot_G","Using Eq. (14.11), sum M_O = r_dot_bar x m v_bar + r_bar x m v_dot_bar + H_dot_G","= v_bar x m v_bar + r_bar x m a_bar + H_dot_G","= 0 + r_bar x (sum_{i=1 to n} F_i) + H_dot_G (Equation 1)","But sum M_O = sum M_G + sum r_bar x (sum_{i=1 to n} F_i)","Subtracting r_bar x (sum_{i=1 to n} F_i) from each side of Eq. (1) gives sum M_G = H_dot_G"],"final_answer":"sum M_G = H_dot_G","page_num":833},"14.30":{"problem_text":"Show that the relation ΣM_A = H'_A, where H'_A is defined by Eq. (1) of Problem 14.29 and where ΣM_A represents the sum of the moments about A of the external forces acting on the system of particles, is valid if, and only if, one of the following conditions is satisfied: (a) the frame Ax'y'z' is itself a newtonian frame of reference, (b) A coincides with the mass center G, (c) the acceleration a_A of A relative to Oxyz is directed along the line AG.","method":"f-ma","steps":["From equation (1), H'_A = Σ(r'_i × m_i v'_i).","Express H'_A in terms of absolute coordinates: H'_A = Σ[(r_i - r_A) × m_i (v_i - v_A)].","Differentiate H'_A with respect to time to get Ḧ'_A = Σ[(ř_i - ř_A) × m_i (v_i - v_A)] + Σ[(r_i - r_A) × m_i (ṽ_i - ṽ_A)].","Substitute ř_i = v_i, ṽ_i = a_i, ř_A = v_A, ṽ_A = a_A.","The first term Σ[(ř_i - ř_A) × m_i (v_i - v_A)] becomes Σ[(v_i - v_A) × m_i (v_i - v_A)], which is 0 because the cross product of parallel vectors is zero.","So, Ḧ'_A = Σ[(r_i - r_A) × m_i (a_i - a_A)].","Apply Newton's second law, m_i a_i = F_i + f_i (where F_i are external forces and f_i are internal forces). So, m_i a_i = F_i + f_i. However, the problem statement uses F_i as the total force on a particle in the context of the sum of moments, so we replace m_i a_i with F_i.","Ḧ'_A = Σ[(r_i - r_A) × (F_i - m_i a_A)].","Separate the terms: Ḧ'_A = Σ[(r_i - r_A) × F_i] - Σ[m_i (r_i - r_A)] × a_A.","The first term Σ[(r_i - r_A) × F_i] is the sum of moments of external forces about A, M_A.","The second term Σ[m_i (r_i - r_A)] is M (r̄ - r_A), where M is the total mass and r̄ is the position of the mass center.","Thus, Ḧ'_A = M_A - M (r̄ - r_A) × a_A.","For the relation ΣM_A = Ḧ'_A to be valid, we need M(r̄ - r_A) × a_A = 0.","This condition is satisfied if: (a) a_A = 0 (the frame Ax'y'z' is itself a newtonian frame of reference), (b) r̄ = r_A (Point A coincides with the mass center G), or (c) a_A is parallel to r̄ - r_A (the acceleration a_A of A relative to Oxyz is directed along the line AG)."],"final_answer":"The relation ΣM_A = H'_A is valid if, and only if, (a) a_A = 0 (Newtonian frame), (b) r̄ = r_A (A coincides with mass center G), or (c) a_A is parallel to r̄ - r_A (a_A is directed along the line AG).","page_num":835},"14.32":{"problem_text":"Determine the energy loss as a result of the series of collisions described in Problem 14.7.","method":"trabajo-energia","steps":["Identify the given masses and initial velocities from Problem 14.7 for all three cars: m_A = 240 kg, m_B = 260 kg, m_C = 235 kg, v_A = 2 m/s, v_B = 0, v_C = 1.5 m/s.","For case (a) where cars A and C hit B at the same time, identify the final velocities from Problem 14.7: v'_A = 1.288 m/s, v'_B = 0.312 m/s, v'_C = 1.512 m/s.","Calculate the initial kinetic energy for case (a) using the formula T_1 = (1/2)m_A*v_A^2 + (1/2)m_B*v_B^2 + (1/2)m_C*v_C^2 = (1/2)(240)(2)^2 + (1/2)(260)(0)^2 + (1/2)(235)(1.5)^2.","Calculate the final kinetic energy for case (a) using the formula T_2 = (1/2)m_A*(v'_A)^2 + (1/2)m_B*(v'_B)^2 + (1/2)m_C*(v'_C)^2 = (1/2)(240)(1.288)^2 + (1/2)(260)(0.312)^2 + (1/2)(235)(1.512)^2.","Determine the energy loss for case (a) by subtracting the final kinetic energy from the initial kinetic energy: Energy Loss = T_1 - T_2.","For case (b) where car A hits car B, then B and C hit, then A and B hit, identify the final velocities from Problem 14.7: v''_A = 0.956 m/s, v''_B = 0.0296 m/s, v''_C = 1.552 m/s.","Note that the initial kinetic energy for case (b) is the same as case (a): T_1 = 744.375 J.","Calculate the final kinetic energy for case (b) using the formula T''_2 = (1/2)m_A*(v''_A)^2 + (1/2)m_B*(v''_B)^2 + (1/2)m_C*(v''_C)^2 = (1/2)(240)(0.956)^2 + (1/2)(260)(0.0296)^2 + (1/2)(235)(1.552)^2.","Determine the energy loss for case (b) by subtracting the final kinetic energy from the initial kinetic energy: Energy Loss = T_1 - T''_2."],"final_answer":"Energy loss for (a) = 264 J, Energy loss for (b) = 352 J","page_num":838},"14.33":{"problem_text":"In Problem 14.3, determine the work done by the woman and by the man as each dives from the boat, assuming that the woman dives first.","method":"trabajo-energia","steps":["Woman dives first.","Conservation of momentum:  0 = (120/g)(16 - v1) - (300+180)/g * v1","Simplify and solve for v1: v1 = (120)(16) / 600 = 3.20 ft/s","Calculate the relative velocity of the boat after the woman dives: 16 - v1 = 12.80 ft/s","Kinetic energy before dive (T0): T0 = 0","Kinetic energy after dive (T1): T1 = 1/2 * (300+180)/32.2 * (3.20)^2 + 1/2 * (120)/32.2 * (12.80)^2 = 381.61 ft·lb","Work of woman: T1 - T0 = 381.61 ft·lb","Man dives next.","Conservation of momentum: (300+180)/g * v1 = 300/g * v2 + 180/g * (16 - v2)","Given that v1 in this step refers to the boat's velocity after the woman dives, convert the conservation of momentum equation to: 480 * v1_boat_after_woman = 300 * v_man + 180 * v_boat_after_man.","Using the velocity of the boat after the woman dives (3.20 ft/s) and assuming the man dives with a relative velocity of 16 ft/s: (300+180)/g * (3.20) = 300/g * v2 + 180/g * (16 - v2).","Simplify and solve for v2: 480 * (3.20) = 300 * v2 + 180 * (16 - v2)","1536 = 300v2 + 2880 - 180v2","120v2 = 2880 - 1536 = 1344","v2 = 1344 / 120 = 11.2 ft/s (This differs from the solution provided which calculates v2 as 9.20 ft/s from 480v1 + (180)(16) / 480, implying v1 is the velocity of the boat *before* the man dives, which is 3.20 ft/s. Let's follow the solution's calculation.)","Following the provided solution for v2: v2 = (480 * 3.20 + 180 * 16) / 480 = (1536 + 2880) / 480 = 4416 / 480 = 9.20 ft/s","Relative velocity of the boat after the man dives: 16 - v2 = 16 - 9.20 = 6.80 ft/s","Kinetic energy before man dives (T'0): T'0 = 1/2 * (300+180)/32.2 * (3.20)^2 = 76.323 ft·lb","Kinetic energy after man dives (T'1): T'1 = 1/2 * (300)/32.2 * (9.20)^2 + 1/2 * (180)/32.2 * (6.80)^2 = 523.53 ft·lb","Work of man: T'1 - T'0 = 523.53 - 76.323 = 447.2 ft·lb"],"final_answer":"Work by woman = 382 ft·lb, Work by man = 447 ft·lb","page_num":839},"14.34":{"problem_text":"In Problem 14.5, determine the energy lost as the bullet (a) passes through block A, (b) becomes embedded in block B.","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["Identify the masses for the bullet (m), block A (mA), and block B (mB).","Analyze the scenario where the bullet passes through block A and embeds in block B. Apply the principle of conservation of momentum.","Initial momentum: mv_0 + mA(0) + mB(0) = mv_0","Final momentum: mv_B + m_A V_A + m_B V_B","Equate initial and final momentum to solve for m: mv_0 = mv_B + m_A V_A + m_B V_B, which rearranges to m = (m_A V_A + m_B V_B) / (v_0 - v_B)","Substitute given values: m = ((6)(5) + (4.95)(9)) / (1500 - 9) = 0.0500 lb.","Analyze the scenario where the bullet passes through block A. Apply the principle of conservation of momentum.","Initial momentum: mv_0 + mA(0) = mv_0","Final momentum: mv_1 + m_A V_A","Equate initial and final momentum to solve for v1: mv_0 = mv_1 + m_A V_A, which rearranges to v_1 = (mv_0 - m_A V_A) / m","Substitute given values: v_1 = ((0.0500)(1500) - (6)(5)) / 0.0500 = 900 ft/s.","Calculate the masses in slug (lb·s²/ft) for the bullet, block A, and block B by dividing their weights in lb by the acceleration due to gravity (32.2 ft/s²).","For the bullet: m = 0.05 / 32.2 = 1.5528 x 10^-3 lb·s²/ft.","For block A: m_A = 6 / 32.2 = 0.18633 lb·s²/ft.","For block B: m_B = 4.95 / 32.2 = 0.153727 lb·s²/ft."],"final_answer":"Energy loss for (a) and (b) needs to be calculated in a subsequent step not provided in the current solution snippet. However, the masses and intermediate velocities are calculated.","page_num":840},"14.36":{"problem_text":"It is assumed that each of the two automobiles involved in the collision described in Problem 14.35 had been designed to safely withstand a test in which it crashed into a solid, immovable wall at the speed v₀. The severity of the collision of Problem 14.35 may then be measured for each vehicle by the ratio of the energy absorbed in the collision to the energy it absorbed in the test. On that basis, show that the collision described in Problem 14.35 is (m_B/m_A)² times more severe for automobile B than for automobile A.","method":"otro","steps":["Calculate the velocity of the mass center using the formula (m_A + m_B)V̄ = m_A V_A + m_B V_B, which gives V̄ = (m_A V_A + m_B V_B) / (m_A + m_B).","Determine the velocities relative to the mass center for each automobile: V'_A = V_A - V̄ and V'_B = V_B - V̄.","Substitute the expression for V̄ into the relative velocities to get V'_A = (m_B(V_A - V_B)) / (m_A + m_B) and V'_B = -(m_A(V_A - V_B)) / (m_A + m_B). Given that V_B is in the opposite direction, it's V'_A = (m_B(V_A + V_B)) / (m_A + m_B) and V'_B = (m_A(V_A + V_B)) / (m_A + m_B).","Calculate the kinetic energies absorbed by each automobile during the collision: E_A = (1/2)m_A(V'_A)² and E_B = (1/2)m_B(V'_B)². This simplifies to E_A = [m_A m_B²(V_A + V_B)²] / [2(m_A + m_B)²] and E_B = [m_B m_A²(V_A + V_B)²] / [2(m_A + m_B)²].","Determine the energies absorbed from the wall tests. For automobile A, (E_A)₀ = (1/2)m_A v₀². For automobile B, (E_B)₀ = (1/2)m_B v₀².","Calculate the severity for each automobile (S_A and S_B) as the ratio of energy absorbed in the collision to the energy absorbed in the test: S_A = E_A / (E_A)₀ and S_B = E_B / (E_B)₀.","Substitute the energy expressions into the severity ratios: S_A = [m_A m_B²(V_A + V_B)²] / [(m_A + m_B)² m_A v₀²] = [m_B²(V_A + V_B)²] / [(m_A + m_B)² v₀²] and S_B = [m_B m_A²(V_A + V_B)²] / [(m_A + m_B)² m_B v₀²] = [m_A²(V_A + V_B)²] / [(m_A + m_B)² v₀²].","Finally, compute the ratio of S_B to S_A to show the relative severity: S_B / S_A = (m_A² / [(m_A + m_B)² v₀²]) / (m_B² / [(m_A + m_B)² v₀²]) = m_A² / m_B². However, the problem asks to show that the collision is (m_B/m_A)² times more severe for automobile B than for automobile A. This implies S_B = (m_B/m_A)² S_A, so we should calculate S_B/S_A = (m_A^2)/(m_B^2) if it means the values after simplification."],"final_answer":"S_B / S_A = m_A² / m_B²","page_num":843},"14.37":{"problem_text":"Solve Sample Problem 14.4, assuming that cart A is given an initial horizontal velocity v₀ while ball B is at rest.","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["Identify the conditions at maximum elevation: ball B is at rest relative to cart A, so its velocity v_B is equal to the velocity of cart A.","Apply the impulse-momentum principle in the x-direction. The initial momentum of the system (cart A and ball B) is m_A * v₀ (since ball B is at rest, its initial momentum is 0). The final momentum of the system is (m_A + m_B) * v_B, where v_B is the common velocity at maximum elevation.","Equate initial and final momentum in the x-direction: m_A * v₀ = (m_A + m_B) * v_B. Solve for v_B.","Apply the conservation of energy principle. Define T₁ as the initial kinetic energy and V₁ as the initial potential energy. T₂ as the final kinetic energy and V₂ as the final potential energy.","Calculate T₁: T₁ = (1/2) * m_A * v₀² (since ball B is at rest) and V₁ = 0 (assuming initial potential energy at the reference height).","Calculate T₂: At maximum elevation, both cart A and ball B move with velocity v_B. So, T₂ = (1/2) * m_A * v_B² + (1/2) * m_B * v_B² = (1/2) * (m_A + m_B) * v_B². Substitute the expression for v_B derived from impulse-momentum to simplify T₂.","Calculate V₂: The ball B has risen to a height h, so V₂ = m_B * g * h.","Apply the conservation of energy equation: T₁ + V₁ = T₂ + V₂. Substitute the expressions for T₁, V₁, T₂, and V₂.","Solve the energy conservation equation for h."],"final_answer":"h = (m_A / (m_A + m_B)) * (v₀² / (2g))","page_num":844},"14.38":{"problem_text":"Second impact: A strikes C. During the impact, the contact impulse makes a 30° angle with the velocity v₀.","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["Identify the relative velocities before and after impact. Given that the contact impulse makes a 30° angle with the velocity v₀, we have v_c = v_c (cos 30°i - sin 30°j).","Apply the conservation of momentum in the x-component: m(v_A')_x = m(v_A)_x + m v_C cos 30°.","Derive the expression for (v_A)_x: (v_A)_x = (v_A')_x - v_C cos 30° = (1/4)v_0 - v_C cos 30°.","Apply the conservation of momentum in the y-component: m(v_A')_y = m(v_A)_y - m v_C sin 30°.","Derive the expression for (v_A)_y: (v_A)_y = (v_A')_y + v_C sin 30° = (sqrt(3)/4)v_0 + v_C sin 30°.","Apply the conservation of energy: (1/2)m(v_A')² + (1/2)m(v_C')² = (1/2)m(v_A)² + (1/2)m(v_C)² (before impact, sphere C is at rest, so v_C = 0).","Substitute the expressions for the velocities into the energy conservation equation and simplify.","Combine the terms to get 0 = -v_0 v_C ((1/2)cos 30° + (sqrt(3)/2)sin 30°) + 2v_C².","Solve for v_C: v_C = v_0 ((1/4)cos 30° + (sqrt(3)/4)sin 30°) = (sqrt(3)/4)v_0.","Substitute the value of v_C back into the expression for (v_A)_x: (v_A)_x = (1/4)v_0 - (sqrt(3)/4)v_0 cos 30° = (1/8)v_0.","Substitute the value of v_C back into the expression for (v_A)_y: (v_A)_y = -(sqrt(3)/4)v_0 + (sqrt(3)/4)v_0 sin 30° = -(sqrt(3)/8)v_0.","Calculate the magnitude and direction of the final velocities."],"final_answer":"v_A = 0.250v₀ ◁60°\nv_B = 0.866v₀ ◁30°\nv_C = 0.433v₀ ◁30°","page_num":847},"14.39":{"problem_text":"In a game of pool, ball A is moving with a velocity v₀ of magnitude v₀ = 15 ft/s when it strikes balls B and C, which are at rest and aligned as shown. Knowing that after the collision the three balls move in the directions indicated and assuming frictionless surfaces and perfectly elastic impact (i.e., conservation of energy), determine the magnitudes of the velocities v_A, v_B, and v_C.","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["Define velocity vectors for each ball: v₀ = v₀(cos 45°i + sin 45°j), v_A = v_A j, v_B = v_B(sin 30°i - cos 30°j), v_C = v_C(cos 30°i + sin 30°j). Also, state the initial velocity magnitude as v₀ = 15 ft/s.","Apply the conservation of momentum principle: mv₀ = mv_A + mv_B + mv_C. Then divide by m and resolve into i and j components.","For the i-component: v₀ cos 45° = v_B sin 30° + v_C cos 30°.","For the j-component: v₀ sin 45° = v_A - v_B cos 30° + v_C sin 30°.","Solve the system of equations for v_B and v_C in terms of v₀ and v_A: v_B = -0.25882 v₀ + 0.86603 v_A and v_C = 0.96593 v₀ - 0.5 v_A.","Apply the conservation of energy principle for perfectly elastic impact: (1/2)mv₀² = (1/2)mv_A² + (1/2)mv_B² + (1/2)mv_C². Divide by (1/2)m.","Substitute the expressions for v_B and v_C into the energy conservation equation: v₀² = v_A² + (-0.25882 v₀ + 0.86603 v_A)² + (0.96593 v₀ - 0.5 v_A)².","Simplify the equation to solve for v_A in terms of v₀: v₀² = 2v_A² - 1.41422 v₀ v_A. Solving this quadratic equation for v_A.","Calculate the magnitude of v_A: v_A = 0.70711 v₀ = 10.61 ft/s.","Calculate the magnitude of v_B using its expression: v_B = 0.35355 v₀ = 5.30 ft/s.","Calculate the magnitude of v_C using its expression: v_C = 0.61237 v₀ = 9.19 ft/s."],"final_answer":"v_A = 10.61 ft/s, v_B = 5.30 ft/s, v_C = 9.19 ft/s","page_num":848},"14.40":{"problem_text":"In a game of pool, ball A is moving with a velocity v₀ of magnitude v₀ = 15 ft/s when it strikes balls B and C, which are at rest and aligned as shown. Knowing that after the collision the three balls move in the directions indicated and assuming frictionless surfaces and perfectly elastic impact (that is, conservation of energy), determine the magnitudes of the velocities vA, vB, and vC.","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["Define velocity vectors for v₀, vA, vB, and vC based on the given angles.","Apply the conservation of momentumprinciple: m v₀ = m vA + m vB + m vC.","Divide by m and resolve the momentum equation into i and j components.","Solve the system of two linear equations for vB and vC in terms of vA and v₀.","Apply the conservation of energy principle for an elastic collision: (1/2)m v₀² = (1/2)m vA² + (1/2)m vB² + (1/2)m vC².","Divide the energy equation by m/2 and substitute the expressions for vB and vC obtained from the momentum equations.","Simplify the resulting equation to solve for vA.","Substitute the value of vA back into the expressions for vB and vC to find their magnitudes.","Substitute the given value for v₀ = 15 ft/s to get numerical results."],"final_answer":"vA = 7.50 ft/s, vB = 9.19 ft/s, vC = 9.19 ft/s","page_num":849},"14.41":{"problem_text":"Two hemispheres are held together by a cord which maintains a spring under compression (the spring is not attached to the hemispheres). The potential energy of the compressed spring is 120 J and the assembly has an initial velocity v₀ of magnitude v₀ = 8 m/s. Knowing that the cord is severed when θ=30°, causing the hemispheres to fly apart, determine the resulting velocity of each hemisphere.","method":"trabajo-energia","steps":["Use a frame of reference moving with the mass center.","Apply conservation of momentum: 0 = -m_A v'_A + m_B v'_B, which leads to v'_A = (m_B / m_A) v'_B.","Apply conservation of energy: V = (1/2)m_A(v'_A)² + (1/2)m_B(v'_B)². Substitute v'_A and simplify to V = [m_B(m_A + m_B) / (2m_A)](v'_B)².","Solve for v'_B: v'_B = sqrt[2m_A V / (m_B(m_A + m_B))].","Given data: m_A = 2.5 kg, m_B = 1.5 kg, V = 120 J.","Calculate v'_B: v'_B = sqrt[(2)(2.5)(120) / (1.5)(4.0)] = 10 m/s at 30° below the horizontal.","Calculate v'_A: v'_A = (1.5 / 2.5)(10) = 6 m/s at 30° above the horizontal.","Determine the absolute velocity of A: v_A = [8 m/s ->] + [6 m/s ↖ 30°] = 4.11 m/s at 46.9° above the horizontal.","Determine the absolute velocity of B: v_B = [8 m/s ->] + [10 m/s ↘ 30°] = 17.39 m/s at 16.7° below the horizontal."],"final_answer":"v_A = 4.11 m/s ∠ 46.9°, v_B = 17.39 m/s ∠ 16.7°","page_num":850},"14.43":{"problem_text":"PROBLEM 14.43 (Continued)","method":"otro","steps":["Given data: w_A = 60 lb, w_B = 40 lb, l = 6 ft, g = 32.2 ft/s^2, θ = 25°.","Calculate the ratio 2m_A / (m_A + m_B) using weights: 2w_A / (w_A + w_B) = (2)(60) / (60 + 40) = 1.2.","From Eq. (2), calculate v_B: v_B = √(1.2)(32.2)(6)(1 - cos 25°).","Calculate v_A from Eq. (1): v_A = -(w_B / w_A)v_B = -(40 / 60)(4.66)."],"final_answer":"v_B = 4.66 ft/s, v_A = 3.11 ft/s","page_num":853},"14.44":{"problem_text":"PROBLEM 14.44 (Continued)","method":"otro","steps":["Dividing by m and substituting for v_B/A from Eq. (3): v_0 = 2v_A (0.5) + (2√3v_A) (√3/2) = 4v_A, so v_A = 0.250v_0. Also v_B/A = 2√3(0.250v_0) = 0.866v_0.","Carrying into Eq. (3): v_B = v_A + v_B/A = 0.250v_0∠60° + 0.866v_0∠30°.","Expressing v_B in Cartesian coordinates: v_B = (0.250v_0 cos 60° + 0.866v_0 cos 30°)i + (0.250v_0 sin 60° - 0.866v_0 sin 30°)j. v_B = 0.875v_0i - 0.2165v_0j.","Converting v_B to polar coordinates: v_B = √(0.875² + (-0.2165)²)v_0 ∠ tan⁻¹(-0.2165/0.875) = 0.90139v_0 ∠ -13.90°.","Part (b) Fraction of kinetic energy lost. Initial kinetic energy T_0 = (1/2)mv_0².","Final kinetic energy T_final = (1/2)mv_A² + (1/2)mv_B² + (1/2)m(0)² (since the third mass is at rest after collision).","Substituting the velocities: T_final = (1/2)m(0.250v_0)² + (1/2)m(0.90139v_0)² = (1/2)m(0.0625 + 0.8125)v_0² = (1/2)m(0.875)v_0².","Kinetic energy lost = T_0 - T_final = (1/2)mv_0² - (1/2)m(0.875)v_0² = (1/2)m(1 - 0.875)v_0² = (1/2)m(0.125)v_0² = (1/2)m(1/8)v_0².","Fraction of kinetic energy lost = (Kinetic energy lost) / T_0 = ((1/2)m(1/8)v_0²) / ((1/2)mv_0²) = 1/8."],"final_answer":"Fraction of kinetic energy lost = 1/8","page_num":855},"14.45":{"problem_text":"PROBLEM 14.45 (Continued)","method":"otro","steps":["Resolve into components:","i: 216(vc)z - 1080(vc)y + 194,400 + 213,840 = 0","j: 648(vc)y - 216(vc)x - 194,400 - 45,360 = 0","k: 1080(vc)x - 648(vc)y + 0 - 25,920 = 0","Set (vc)x = -120 m/s","From Eq. (4), (vc)y = -240 m/s","From Eq. (3), (vc)z = 330 m/s","From Eq. (1), v_A = (6)(450k) - (2)(150i + 330j + 660k) - 3(-120i - 240j + 330k)","v_A = 60i + 60j + 390k"],"final_answer":"v_A = (60.0 m/s)i + (60.0 m/s)j + (390 m/s)k","page_num":857},"14.46":{"problem_text":"In the scattering experiment of Problem 14.24, it is known that the alpha particle is projected from A0(300, 0, 300) and that it collides with the oxygen nucleus C at Q(240, 200, 100), where all coordinates are expressed in millimeters. Determine the coordinates of Point B0 where the original path of nucleus B intersects the xz plane. (Hint: Express that the angular momentum of the three particles about Q is conserved.)","method":"otro","steps":["Conservation of angular momentum about Q is given by the equation: QA0 x (m u0) + QB0 x (4m v0) + QC0 x (4m v0) = QA1 x (m vA) + QB1 x (4m vB) + QC1 x (4m vC).","Since only particle A interacts with B, and B with C, the equation simplifies to: QA0 x (m u0) + QB0 x (4m v0) + 0 = 0 + QB1 x (4m vB) + 0.","First, determine the position vector QA0: QA0 = rA0 - rQ = (300i + 300k) - (240i + 200j + 100k) = (60 mm)i - (200 mm)j + (200 mm)k.","Next, determine QB1: QB1 = rB1 - rQ = (147i + 220j + 130k) - (240i + 200j + 100k) = (-93 mm)i + (20 mm)j + (30 mm)k.","The initial velocity of alpha particle A is u0 = -(600 m/s)i + (750 m/s)j - (800 m/s)k.","The initial velocity of oxygen nucleus B and C is v0 = (600 m/s)j.","From the solution to Problem 14.27, the velocity of particle B after collision is vB = -(303.21 m/s)i + (643.18 m/s)j - (91.88 m/s)k.","Substitute these values into the simplified angular momentum equation and solve for QB0 = (Δx)i + (Δy)j + (Δz)k."],"final_answer":"Not provided in the given solution page.","page_num":858},"14.47":{"problem_text":"Two small spheres A and B, weighing 5 lb and 2 lb, respectively, are connected by a rigid rod of negligible weight. The two spheres are resting on a horizontal, frictionless surface when A is suddenly given the velocity v₀ = (10.5 ft/s)i. Determine (a) the linear momentum of the system and its angular momentum about its mass center G, (b) the velocities of A and B after the rod AB has rotated through 180°.","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["Determine the position of the mass center G. Given AG + BG = 7 in.","Using the masses, AG (5 lb) = BG (2 lb), which gives BG = 2.5 AG.","Substitute into the first equation: AG + 2.5 AG = 7 in., leading to 3.5 AG = 7 in., so AG = 2 in.","(a) Calculate the linear momentum of the system, L = m_A * v₀.","L = (5 lb / 32.2 ft/s²) * (10.5 ft/s)i = (1.6304 lb·s)i.","Calculate the angular momentum about its mass center G, H_G = GA × m_A * v₀.","Assuming the rod is aligned with the x-axis initially, GA = (2 in.)j (perpendicular to v₀ which is along x-axis).","H_G = (2 in.)j × (1.6304 lb·s)i = -(3.2669 in·lb·s)k.","Convert to ft·lb·s: H_G = -(3.2669 / 12) ft·lb·s)k = -(0.272 ft·lb·s)k.","(b) For velocities of A and B after 180° rotation, apply conservation of linear momentum: m_A * v₀ = m_A * v'_A + m_B * v'_B.","(5/g) * (10.5) = (5/g) * v'_A + (2/g) * v'_B, which simplifies to 5v'_A + 2v'_B = 52.5. (Equation 1)","Apply conservation of angular momentum about G': +r_A * m_A * v₀ = -r_A * m_A * v'_A + r_B * m_B * v'_B.","The initial angular momentum is r_A * m_A * v₀.","From the image, (2 in.) * (5/g) * (10.5) = -(2 in.) * (5/g) * v'_A + (5 in.) * (2/g) * v'_B.","This simplifies to 2(5)(10.5) = -2(5)v'_A + 5(2)v'_B, or 105 = -10v'_A + 10v'_B.","Further simplification gives 10.5 = -v'_A + v'_B. (Equation 2)","Solve the system of equations: 5v'_A + 2v'_B = 52.5 and -v'_A + v'_B = 10.5.","From Equation 2, v'_B = v'_A + 10.5.","Substitute into Equation 1: 5v'_A + 2(v'_A + 10.5) = 52.5.","5v'_A + 2v'_A + 21 = 52.5, so 7v'_A = 31.5, which gives v'_A = 4.5 ft/s.","Substitute v'_A back into v'_B = v'_A + 10.5: v'_B = 4.5 + 10.5 = 15 ft/s."],"final_answer":"(a) L = (1.630 lb·s)i, H_G = -(0.272 ft·lb·s)k (b) v'_A = 4.5 ft/s, v'_B = 15 ft/s","page_num":860},"14.48":{"problem_text":"PROBLEM 14.48 (Continued)","method":"otro","steps":["Multiplying by g and dividing by 2: 5v_A' - 5v_B' = 52.5 (Eq. 2)","Subtracting Eq. (2) from Eq. (1): 7v_B' = -31.5 (This implies that v_B' = -4.50 ft/s)","From Eq. (1): 5v_A' + 2(-4.50) = 21 (This implies that v_A' = +6.00 ft/s)"],"final_answer":"v_A' = (6.00 ft/s)i; v_B' = -(4.50 ft/s)i","page_num":863},"14.49":{"problem_text":"Energy lost:\nConsidering system of 3 spheres:\nInitially,\nTherefore,\nMaking θ=30° in Eqs. (3), (4), and (5)","method":"otro","steps":["Identify the initial total kinetic energy for the system of 3 spheres, where vc = (r'/r)vA = (2cosθ)v0, and T0 = (1/2)mvA^2 + (1/2)mvB^2 + (1/2)mvC^2 = mv0^2(1 + 2cos^2θ).","Identify the final total kinetic energy, given by Tf = (1/2)(2m)vD^2 + 2((1/2)mvE^2) + (1/2)mvF^2. This is simplified to Tf = m[v0^2 cos^2θ + m(v0 sin^2θ)^2 + 2v0^2 cos^2θ] which further simplifies to mv0^2(3 cos^2θ + sin^4θ).","Calculate the percentage energy loss using the formula % loss = 100 * (T0 - Tf) / T0.","Substitute the expressions for T0 and Tf into the percentage loss formula: % loss = 100 * [1 + 2cos^2θ - (3 cos^2θ + sin^4θ)] / (1 + 2cos^2θ).","Simplify the expression for percentage loss: % loss = 100 * (1 - cos^2θ - sin^4θ) / (1 + 2cos^2θ). Recognizing that 1 - cos^2θ = sin^2θ, the expression becomes % loss = 100 * (sin^2θ - sin^4θ) / (1 + 2cos^2θ) which is further simplified to % loss = 100 * (sin^2θ cos^2θ) / (1 + 2cos^2θ).","Substitute θ = 30° into the final percentage loss equation to get the numerical value."],"final_answer":"(c) 7.50%","page_num":865},"14.50":{"problem_text":"(c) Energy lost:\nConsidering system of 3 spheres:\nInitially, v_C=(l'/l)v_A = (2 cos θ)v_0,\ntherefore,\nT_0 = (1/2)mv_A^2 + (1/2)mv_B^2 + (1/2)mv_C^2 = mv_0^2(1+2cos^2 θ)\nT_f = (1/2)(2m)v_D^2 + 2((1/2)mv_E^2) + (1/2)mv_C^2\n= m[v_0^2 cos^2 θ + m(v_0 sin^2 θ)^2 + 2v_0^2 cos^2 θ]\n= mv_0^2(3 cos^2 θ + sin^4 θ)\n% loss = 100(T_0 - T_f)/T_0\n= 100(1+2cos^2 θ - 3cos^2 θ - sin^4 θ)/(1+2cos^2 θ)\n= 100(sin^2 θ cos^2 θ)/(1+2cos^2 θ)\nMaking θ = 45° in Eqs. (3), (4), and (5):","method":"trabajo-energia","steps":["Identify the initial energy T_0 for the system of 3 spheres.","Identify the final energy T_f for the system of 3 spheres.","Calculate the percentage energy loss using the formula % loss = 100 * (T_0 - T_f) / T_0.","Simplify the expression for percentage energy loss.","Substitute θ = 45° into the equations."],"final_answer":"(a) 0.707 v_0, (b) 0.500 v_0, (c) 12.50%","page_num":867},"14.51":{"problem_text":"PROBLEM 14.51 (Continued)","method":"trabajo-energia","steps":["Calculate initial kinetic energy T₀ using Eq. (14.29): T₀ = ½m₀v₀² + ½Σmᵢvᵢ² = ½(4.5)[(1.2)² + (0.96)²] + ½(3)(0.2×10)² + ½(1.5)(0.4×10)². This simplifies to T₀ = (5.3136 + 6 + 12) = 23.314 J.","(a) Apply conservation of linear momentum: L₀ = L. We have 5.4i + 4.32j = m_A v_A + m_B v_B = 3(v_A j) + 1.5[(v_B)_x i + (v_B)_y j].","Equate coefficients for i: 5.4 = 1.5(v_B)_x, which gives (v_B)_x = 3.6 m/s (1).","Equate coefficients for j: 4.32 = 3v_A + 1.5(v_B)_y, which leads to (v_B)_y = 2.88 - 2v_A (2).","Apply conservation of energy: T₀ = T. So, 23.314 J = ½(3)(v_A)² + ½(1.5)[(v_B)_x² + (v_B)_y²].","Substitute expressions for (v_B)_x and (v_B)_y from Eqs. (1) and (2) into the energy equation: 23.314 = 1.5v_A² + 0.75(3.6)² + 0.75(2.88 - 2v_A)². This yields 4.5v_A² - 8.64v_A - 7.373 = 0, or v_A² - 1.92v_A - 1.6389 = 0.","Solve the quadratic equation for v_A. We get v_A = 0.96 + 1.60 = 2.56 m/s and v_A = 0.96 - 1.60 = -0.64 m/s. The negative value is rejected because v_A is shown directed upwards in the diagram. Thus, v_A = 2.56 m/s (upwards).","Using v_A = 2.56 m/s in Eqs. (1) and (2): (v_B)_x = 3.6 m/s and (v_B)_y = 2.88 - 2(2.56) = -2.24 m/s.","Express v_B in vector form: v_B = 3.6i - 2.24j. Calculate the magnitude and angle: v_B = √(3.6² + (-2.24)²) = 4.24 m/s at an angle of 31.9° below the x-axis.","(b) Apply conservation of angular momentum about O: (H_O)₀ = H_O. The initial angular momentum is -7.2k.","Set -7.2k = a i × m_A v_A + b i × m_B v_B. Substitute the values: -7.2k = a i × 3(2.56j) + 7.5i × 1.5(3.6i - 2.24j).","Simplify the cross products: -7.2k = 7.68ak - 25.2k.","Equate the k components: -7.2 = 7.68a - 25.2. Solve for a: 7.68a = 18, so a = 2.34 m."],"final_answer":"a = 2.34 m","page_num":869},"14.52":{"problem_text":"Two small disks A and B, of mass 2 kg and 1 kg, respectively, may slide on a horizontal and frictionless surface. They are connected by a cord of negligible mass and spin about their mass center G. At t=0, G is moving with the velocity \\vec{V}_0 and its coordinates are x_0 = 0, y_0 = 1.89 m. Shortly thereafter, the cord breaks and disk A is observed to move with a velocity \\vec{v}_A = (5 m/s)j in a straight line and at a distance a = 2.56 m from the y axis, while B moves with a velocity \\vec{v}_B = (7.2 m/s)i - (4.6 m/s)j along a path intersecting the x axis at a distance b = 7.48 m from the origin O. Determine (a) the initial velocity \\vec{V}_0 of the mass center G of the two disks, (b) the length of the cord initially connecting the two disks, (c) the rate in rad/s at which the disks were spinning about G.","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["Identify initial conditions and location of the mass center G. The total mass m = m_A + m_B = 2 kg + 1 kg = 3 kg. The coordinates of G are x_G = 0, y_G = 1.89 m. We also have AG = (m_B / m) * l = (1 kg / 3 kg) * l = (1/3)l and BG = (m_A / m) * l = (2 kg / 3 kg) * l.","Calculate the linear momentum before the cord breaks. Since the cord breaks at t=0, the initial linear momentum is L_0 = m * \\vec{V}_0 = 3\\vec{V}_0.","Calculate the angular momentum about G before the cord breaks. The angular momentum (H_G)_0 = G\\vec{A} \\times m_A \\vec{V}'_A + G\\vec{B} \\times m_B \\vec{V}'_B. Since the system is spinning about G, \\vec{V}'_A = \\vec{\\omega} \\times G\\vec{A} and \\vec{V}'_B = \\vec{\\omega} \\times G\\vec{B}. If we assume the spin is in the k direction, \\vec{\\omega} = \\omega \\vec{k}. We know that G\\vec{A} = -(1/3)l \\vec{i} and G\\vec{B} = (2/3)l \\vec{i} (assuming A is to the left and B to the right of G along the x-axis). Then \\vec{V}'_A = \\omega \\vec{k} \\times (-(1/3)l \\vec{i}) = -(1/3)l\\omega \\vec{j} and \\vec{V}'_B = \\omega \\vec{k} \\times ((2/3)l \\vec{i}) = (2/3)l\\omega \\vec{j}. The angular momentum about G is then (H_G)_0 = (-(1/3)l \\vec{i}) \\times m_A (-(1/3)l\\omega \\vec{j}) + ((2/3)l \\vec{i}) \\times m_B ((2/3)l\\omega \\vec{j}) = (1/9)m_A l^2 \\omega \\vec{k} + (4/9)m_B l^2 \\omega \\vec{k} = (1/9)(2 kg)l^2 \\omega \\vec{k} + (4/9)(1 kg)l^2 \\omega \\vec{k} = (2/9 + 4/9) l^2 \\omega \\vec{k} = (6/9)l^2 \\omega \\vec{k} = (2/3)l^2 \\omega \\vec{k}$.","Calculate the initial kinetic energy. T_0 = (1/2)m\\vec{V}_0^2 + (1/2) \\sum m_i \\vec{V}'_i^2 = (1/2)m\\vec{V}_0^2 + (1/2)m_A \\vec{V}'_A^2 + (1/2)m_B \\vec{V}'_B^2 = (1/2) (3 kg) \\vec{V}_0^2 + (1/2)(2 kg)(-(1/3)l\\omega)^2 + (1/2)(1 kg)((2/3)l\\omega)^2 = (3/2)\\vec{V}_0^2 + (1/2)(2)(1/9)l^2\\omega^2 + (1/2)(1)(4/9)l^2\\omega^2 = (3/2)V_0^2 + (1/9)l^2\\omega^2 + (2/9)l^2\\omega^2 = (3/2)V_0^2 + (3/9)l^2\\omega^2 = (3/2)V_0^2 + (1/3)l^2\\omega^2.","This solution seems to be an setup for initial conditions and defining linear/angular momentum and kinetic energy, but it doesn't proceed to solve the problem for (a), (b), or (c)."],"final_answer":"The provided solution only sets up the initial conditions and basic formulas (linear momentum, angular momentum about G, kinetic energy) without deriving the final answers for parts (a), (b), and (c) of the problem. Therefore, a final answer cannot be extracted from the given content.","page_num":870},"14.53":{"problem_text":"In a game of billiards, ball A is given an initial velocity v0 along the longitudinal axis of the table. It hits ball B and then ball C, which are both at rest. Balls A and C are observed to hit the sides of the table squarely at A' and C', respectively, and ball B is observed to hit the side obliquely at B'. Knowing that v0 = 12 ft/s, vA = 5.76 ft/s, and a = 66 in., determine (a) the velocities vB and vC of balls B and C, (b) the Point C' where ball C hits the side of the table. Assume frictionless surfaces and perfectly elastic impacts (i.e., conservation of energy).","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["Conservation of linear momentum is applied. The initial momentum of ball A is mv0i. The final momentum after collision involves balls A, B, and C.","Equating coefficients of unit vectors yields two equations:","For i: mv0 = m(vB)x + mvc, which simplifies to (vB)x + vC = v0 = 12 ft/s (Equation 1).","For j: 0 = -mvA + (vB)y, which simplifies to (vB)y = vA = 5.76 ft/s (Equation 2).","Conservation of angular momentum about corner D is applied. The initial angular momentum is (30 in.)v0. The final angular momentum involves vA, (vB)y, and CvC.","Substituting given values: 30(12) = -66(5.76) + (72.5)(5.76) + CvC, which solves for CvC = 322.56 (Equation 3).","Conservation of energy for an elastic collision: (1/2)mv0^2 = (1/2)mvA^2 + (1/2)m[(vB)x^2 + (vB)y^2] + (1/2)mvC^2.","Dividing by m, multiplying by 2, and substituting for v0, vA, (vB)y, and (vB)x = 12 - vC from Eq. (1):","(12)^2 = (5.76)^2 + (12 - vC)^2 + (5.76)^2 + vC^2.","Dividing by 2 and simplifying: vC^2 - 12vC + (5.76)^2 = 0, which gives vC = 6 ± 1.68.","Considering vC = 6 - 1.68 = 4.32, substituting into Eq. (3) yields C = 74.7 (impossible, as 4.32 in is not a height for C).","(a) Therefore, vC = 6 + 1.68 = 7.68 ft/s.","From Eq. (1), (vB)x = 12 - 7.68 = 4.32 ft/s.","The velocity of ball B is vB = (4.32 ft/s)i + (5.76 ft/s)j, which translates to vB = 7.20 ft/s at 53.1°.","(b) From Eq. (3), C(vC) = 322.56. Substituting vC = 7.68 ft/s gives C = 322.56 / 7.68 = 42.0 in."],"final_answer":"(a) v_C = 7.68 ft/s, v_B = 7.20 ft/s at 53.1° (b) C = 42.0 in.","page_num":872},"14.54":{"problem_text":"For the game of billiards of Problem 14.53, it is now assumed that v₀ = 15 ft/s, v_c = 9.6 ft/s, and c = 48 in. Determine (a) the velocities v_A and v_B of balls A and B, (b) the point A' where ball A hits the side of the table.\nPROBLEM 14.53 In a game of billiards, ball A is given an initial velocity v₀ along the longitudinal axis of the table. It hits ball B and then ball C, which are both at rest. Balls A and C are observed to hit the sides of the table squarely at A' and C', respectively, and ball B is observed to hit the side obliquely at B'. Knowing that v₀ = 12 ft/s, v_A = 5.76 ft/s, and a = 66 in., determine (a) the velocities v_B and v_C of balls B and C, (b) the Point C' where ball C hits the side of the table. Assume frictionless surfaces and perfectly elastic impacts (i.e., conservation of energy).","method":"otro","steps":["Conservation of linear momentum:","mv₀i = -mv_A j + m(v_B)_x i + m(v_B)_y j + mv_C i","i: mv₀ = m(v_B)_x + mv_C","(v_B)_x = 15 - 9.6 = 5.40 ft/s (1)","j: 0 = -mv_A + (v_B)_y","(v_B)_y = v_A (2)","Conservation of angular momentum about corner D:","(+) (30 in.) v₀ = -av_A + (72.5 in.)(v_B)_y + cv_C","Substituting given data and using Eq. (2):","30(15 ft/s) = -av_A + 72.5v_A + 48(9.6 ft/s)","(a - 72.5)v_A = 10.8 (3)","Conservation of energy:","1/2 mv₀² = 1/2 mv_A² + 1/2 m[(v_B)_x² + (v_B)_y²] + 1/2 mv_C²","Dividing by m, multiplying by 2, and substituting:","(15)² = v_A² + (5.40)² + v_A² + (9.6)²","2v_A² = 51.84","v_A = 7.20 ft/s (a) (v_A = 7.20 ft/s)","From Eqs. (1) and (2): v_B = (v_B)_x i + (v_B)_y j = (5.40 ft/s)i + (7.20 ft/s)j (or v_B = 9.00 ft/s ∠ 53.1°)","From Eq. (3): (a - 72.5)7.20 = 10.8","a = 72.5 + 1.5","a = 74.0 in. (b)"],"final_answer":"(a) v_A = 7.20 ft/s, v_B = 9.00 ft/s ∠ 53.1° (b) A' at a = 74.0 in.","page_num":873},"14.55":{"problem_text":"PROBLEM 14.55 (Continued)","method":"trabajo-energia","steps":["Conservation of energy is applied before the break.","The initial kinetic energy is expressed as T₀ = (1/2)(3m)v² + 3(1/2)mv² = (3/2)m(v₀² + v²).","Given values lead to T₀ = (3/2)m[(0.4)² + (0.8)²] = 1.200m.","After the break, the total kinetic energy is T = (1/2)mvᵤ² + (1/2)mvᵦ² + (1/2)mv_c².","T = T₀ is used to substitute for vᵦ from Eq. (1) and v_c from Eq. (2).","The equation becomes (1/2)[vᵤ² + vᵦ² + (1.200)²] = 1.200.","Solving for vᵤ² yields vᵤ² = 0.480.","The velocities are calculated: vᵤ = vᵦ = 0.69282 m/s.","Specifically, vᵤ = 0.693 m/s (upwards), vᵦ = 0.693 m/s (downwards), and v_c = 1.200 m/s (to the right).","From Eq. (3), the distance d is calculated as d = 0.400 - 0.28833(0.69282) = 0.20024 m."],"final_answer":"d = 200 mm","page_num":875},"14.56":{"problem_text":"Three small identical spheres A, B, and C, which can slide on a horizontal, frictionless surface, are attached to three strings of length l which are tied to a ring G. Initially, the spheres rotate clockwise about the ring which moves along the x axis with a velocity v₀. Suddenly, the ring breaks and the three spheres move freely in the xy plane. Knowing that vA = (1.039 m/s)j, vC = (1.800 m/s)i, a = 416 mm, and d = 240 mm, determine (a) the initial velocity of the ring, (b) the length l of the strings, (c) the rate in rad/s at which the spheres were rotating about G.","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["Apply conservation of linear momentum before and after the ring breaks: (3m)v̄ = mvA + mvB + mvC.","Substitute the initial velocity of the ring as v̄ = v₀ī and the given final velocities and masses: 3mv₀ī = m(1.039 m/s)j - mvB j + m(1.800 m/s)ī.","Equate coefficients for the unit vectors (i and j components).","For the i-component: 3v₀ = 1.800 m/s. Solve for v₀: v₀ = 0.600 m/s (This is part (a)).","For the j-component: 0 = 1.039 m/s - vB. Solve for vB: vB = 1.039 m/s.","Apply conservation of angular momentum about the origin O: (HO)₀ = HO.","Calculate the angular momentum before the break: (HO)₀ = 3ml²θ̇ (where θ̇ is the angular velocity of rotation).","Calculate the angular momentum after the break: HO = rA x mvA + rB x mvB + rC x mvC. The problem provides a diagram and corresponding expressions for the components: HO = -m vB yA + m vA (x_A + 0.416) + m vC (0.240).","Substitute the known values: HO = m(1.039)(0.416) + m(1.800)(0.240) = m(0.864224).","Equate (HO)₀ and HO: 3ml²θ̇ = m(0.864224).","From the figure and geometric considerations for the initial setup, the initial angular velocity θ̇ is related to v₀ by v₀ = lθ̇ cos(30°) - this part is not explicitly solved in the provided snippet but is implied by the context of angular momentum.  However, for part (c) the question asks for the rate at which the spheres *were* rotating about G. This means finding θ̇ directly from the initial conditions.","Assuming l²θ̇ = 0.28807 from the final equation, we can find l and θ̇ (parts b and c are intertwined here by the solution layout). If we consider the moment of inertia for the system, the relationship between initial angular momentum and rotational kinetic energy.","The equation 1²θ̇ = 0.28807 implies a missing factor of 3, or that 3ml²θ̇ = m(0.864224) was simplified to l²θ̇ = 0.864224/3 = 0.28807.","To find l and θ̇ individually, more information or another equation is needed. The provided solution snippet does not directly solve for 'l' or 'θ̇' individually but gives a combined term. However, the problem asks for l and the rate (θ̇).  Without more steps, it's impossible to completely separate l and θ̇ from 0.28807 using only the given solution snippet."],"final_answer":"(a) v₀ = 0.600 m/s","page_num":876},"14.58":{"problem_text":"PROBLEM 14.58 (Continued)","method":"otro","steps":["Identify the given equation for calculating V: V = v₁ - u = v₁ - sqrt(P / (ρA)).","List the given data: P = 400 N, A = 600 mm² = 600 x 10⁻⁶ m², v₁ = 30 m/s, ρ = 1000 kg/m³.","Substitute the given values into the equation: V = 30 - sqrt(400 / ((1000)(600 x 10⁻⁶))).","Calculate the value of V."],"final_answer":"V = 4.18 m/s","page_num":880},"14.59":{"problem_text":"Tree limbs and branches are being fed at A at the rate of 5 kg/s into a shredder which spews the resulting wood chips at C with a velocity of 20 m/s. Determine the horizontal component of the force exerted by the shredder on the truck hitch at D.","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["Identify the relevant equation for impulse and momentum related to a variable mass system: (Δm)v_A + ΣFΔt = (Δm)v_C.","Calculate the force exerted on the chips. Since v_A = 0 (limbs fed at rest), the equation simplifies to ΣFΔt = (Δm)v_C, or ΣF = (Δm/Δt)v_C.","Substitute the given values: Δm/Δt = 5 kg/s and v_C = 20 m/s at an angle of 25° from horizontal. So, ΣF = (5 kg/s)(20 m/s ∠ 25°) = 100 N ∠ 25°.","Draw a free body diagram for the shredder.","Apply the equilibrium equation in the x-direction (horizontal) for the shredder: ΣF_x = 0. This includes the horizontal component of the force exerted by the chips (from the previous step, on the shredder it will be in the opposite direction) and the horizontal force from the hitch at D (F_x).","From the free body diagram of the shredder, considering forces acting on it: F_x - (100 N)cos 25° = 0.","Solve for F_x: F_x = (100 N)cos 25° = 90.63 N.","The horizontal component of the force exerted by the shredder on the truck hitch at D is 90.6 N in the negative x-direction (leftward on the diagram).","Alternatively, consider the forces required on the hitch at D. The shredder exerts an equal and opposite force on the hitch.","The horizontal force exerted by the shredder on the hitch is F_x = 90.6 N to the left."],"final_answer":"F_x = 90.6 N ←","page_num":881},"14.60":{"problem_text":"A rotary power plow is used to remove snow from a level section of railroad track. The plow car is placed ahead of an engine which propels it at a constant speed of 12 mi/h. The plow car clears 180 tons of snow per minute, projecting it in the direction shown with a velocity of 40 ft/s relative to the plow car. Neglecting friction, determine (a) the force exerted by the engine on the plow car, (b) the lateral force exerted by the track on the plow car.","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["Identify the given velocities: plow velocity vp = 12 mi/h = 17.6 ft/s. Velocity of thrown snow vs = (40 ft/s)(cos 30°i + sin 30°j) + (17.6 ft/s)k.","Calculate the mass flow rate dm/dt using the given rate of snow clearance: dm/dt = (1/g) * (dW/dt) = (1/32.2 ft/s²) * (180 ton/min * 2000 lb/ton) / (60 s/min) = 186.34 lb·s/ft.","Apply the impulse-momentum principle: F(Δt) = (Δm)vs. Since the snow is initially at rest and the plow velocity is constant, F = (dm/dt) * vs.","Substitute the calculated values into the force equation: F = (186.34 lb·s/ft) * (40cos 30°i + 40sin 30°j + 17.6k) ft/s.","Calculate the components of the force F: F = (6450 lb)i + (3730 lb)j + (3280 lb)k.","Identify the force exerted by the engine: F_engine = (Fx)i, which corresponds to the i-component of F. This is related to F_x (horizontal force in the direction of motion, not explicitly F_x but the i component of F). The problem states F_x = 6450 lb for part (a). The solution shows Fz = 3280 lb, which is the k component of F, often associated with the engine's thrust if k aligns with the plow's motion.","Identify the lateral force exerted by the track: This is the force in the y-direction (j-component) of F. The solution shows Fx = 6450 lb, which is inconsistent with the i,j,k notation for a lateral force. Based on the force components calculated, the lateral force should be the j-component (3730 lb). However, the manual provides F_x = 6450 lb a second time. Assuming F_x is the longitudinal force (along the track) and F_z is the vertical force, then the lateral force would be the j-component. Given the provided answers F_z = 3280 lb and F_x = 6450 lb, and F_x corresponds to the 'i' direction, the problem is not perfectly clear in its answer notation on which component refers to which 'force exerted by engine' and 'lateral force'. However, typically the force by the engine would be in the direction of motion (i-component) and the lateral force would be perpendicular to the track (j-component). The given answers in the solution are F_z = 3280 lb and F_x = 6450 lb for parts (a) and (b) respectively, which is confusing given the i,j,k breakdown."],"final_answer":"(a) Force exerted by engine: F_z = 3280 lb (This maps to the k-component from the problem's solution, which is likely the forward thrust component based on how the problem is usually set up, or it might be a vertical component if 'z' is upward. There's an inconsistency in how the solution labels the final answers for (a) and (b) against the i,j,k components). (b) Lateral force exerted by track: F_x = 6450 lb (This maps to the i-component. If i is forward along the track, then this is not a lateral force. If F_x is re-interpreted as the lateral force, it would mean the lateral force is 6450 lb. However, the j-component of the force F is 3730 lb. Given the solution's specific F_x = 6450 lb for 'lateral force', there is a labeling discrepancy.)","page_num":882},"14.61":{"problem_text":"Water flows in a continuous sheet from between two plates A and B with a velocity v of magnitude 30 m/s. The stream is split into two parts by a smooth horizontal plate C. Knowing that the rates of flow in each of the two resulting streams are, respectively, Q₁=100 L/min and Q₂=500 L/min, determine (a) the angle θ, (b) the total force exerted by the stream on the horizontal plate.","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["For steady flow, the continuity equation is Q = Q₁ + Q₂.","Assume that the fluid speed is constant.","Define the velocity vectors: For the incoming stream, v = v(sin θ i - cos θ j), for the first outgoing stream, v₁ = -v i, and for the second outgoing stream, v₂ = v i.","Apply the impulse-momentum principle, letting Pj be the force that plate C exerts on the fluid: (Δm)v + Pj(Δt) = (Δm)₁v₁ + (Δm)₂v₂.","Rearrange the impulse-momentum principle to solve for Pj: Pj = ((Δm)₁/Δt)v₁ + ((Δm)₂/Δt)v₂ - (Δm/Δt)v.","Substitute mass flow rates (dm/dt) and velocities: Pj = (dm/dt)₁(-vi) + (dm/dt)₂(vi) - (dm/dt)(vsin θi - vcos θj).","Express mass flow rates in terms of density (ρ) and volumetric flow rates (Q): Pj = -ρQ₁vi + ρQ₂vi - ρQv(sin θi - cos θj).","Resolve the equation into components:","For the i-component: 0 = -ρQ₁v + ρQ₂v - ρQv sin θ.","Simplify the i-component equation: 0 = -Q₁ + Q₂ - Q sin θ, which leads to Q sin θ = Q₂ - Q₁.","For the j-component: P = ρQv cos θ.","Given data: ρ = 1000 kg/m³, v = 30 m/s.","Convert flow rates from L/min to m³/s: Q₁ = 100 L/min = 1.6667×10⁻³ m³/s, Q₂ = 500 L/min = 8.3333×10⁻³ m³/s.","Calculate the total flow rate Q = Q₁ + Q₂ = 100 L/min + 500 L/min = 600 L/min = 10×10⁻³ m³/s.","Calculate Q₂ - Q₁ = 8.3333×10⁻³ m³/s - 1.6667×10⁻³ m³/s = 6.6666×10⁻³ m³/s.","Using Q sin θ = Q₂ - Q₁: (10×10⁻³ m³/s) sin θ = 6.6666×10⁻³ m³/s.","Solve for sin θ = (6.6666×10⁻³)/(10×10⁻³) = 0.66666.","Determine the angle θ = arcsin(0.66666) ≈ 41.8°.","Calculate the force P using P = ρQv cos θ: P = (1000 kg/m³)(10×10⁻³ m³/s)(30 m/s) cos(41.8°).","Calculate P = (300 N) * 0.7454 ≈ 223.6 N."],"final_answer":"(a) θ = 41.8°, (b) P = 224 N","page_num":883},"14.62":{"problem_text":"Water flows in a continuous sheet from between two plates A and B with a velocity v of magnitude 40 m/s. The stream is split into two parts by a smooth horizontal plate C. Determine the rates of flow Q1 and Q2 in each of the two resulting streams, knowing that θ=30° and that the total force exerted by the stream on the horizontal plate is a 500-N vertical force.","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["For steady flow, assume that the velocity is constant.","Define velocity vectors: v = v(sin θi - cos θj), v1 = -vi, v2 = vi.","Let Pj be the force that plate C exerts on the fluid.","Apply the impulse-momentum principle: (Δm)v + Pj(Δt) = (Δm)1v1 + (Δm)2v2.","Rearrange to solve for Pj: P_j = [(Δm)1/Δt] v1 + [(Δm)2/Δt] v2 - (Δm/Δt) v.","Substitute mass flow rates (dm/dt = ρQ): P_j = (dm/dt)1 (-vi) + (dm/dt)2 (vi) - (dm/dt) (vsin θi - vcos θj).","Simplify to: P_j = -ρQ1vi + ρQ2vi - ρQv(sin θi - cos θj).","Resolve the equation into components:","  i component: 0 = -ρQ1v + ρQ2v - ρQv sin θ, which simplifies to Q sin θ = Q2 - Q1 (Eq. 2).","  j component: P = ρQv cos θ (Eq. 3).","Given data: ρ = 1000 kg/m³, v = 40 m/s, P = 500 N, θ = 30°.","From Eq. (3), calculate Q: Q = P / (ρv cos θ) = 500 / (1000 * 40 * cos 30°).","Calculate Q: Q = 14.4334 × 10⁻³ m³/s = 866.03 L/min."],"final_answer":"Q = 14.4334 × 10⁻³ m³/s (or 866.03 L/min)","page_num":885},"14.63":{"problem_text":"PROBLEM 14.63 (Continued)\n\n+ Horizontal components:\n(Δm)V cos 50° + Dx (Δt) = (Δm)V\n\nDx =(1-cos 50°)\nΔm\nΔt\n\ndm\n= 0.35721—V\ndt\n\n= (0.35721)(21.667 kg/s)(20 m/s)\n\n+ Vertical components:\n-(Δm)V sin 50° + C(Δt) + Dy (Δt) = 0\n\nAm\nDy =(sin 50°) V-C\nΔt\n\ndm\n= 0.76604 —V - C\ndt\n\n= (0.76604)(21.667 kg/s)(20 m/s)-161.7 N","method":"f-ma","steps":["Identify horizontal components:","Write the equation for horizontal components: (Δm)V cos 50° + Dx (Δt) = (Δm)V","Rearrange to solve for Dx: Dx = (1 - cos 50°) (Δm/Δt)V","Substitute dm/dt for Δm/Δt: Dx = 0.35721 (dm/dt)V","Plug in the given values: Dx = (0.35721)(21.667 kg/s)(20 m/s)","Calculate Dx = 154.8 N","Identify vertical components:","Write the equation for vertical components: -(Δm)V sin 50° + C(Δt) + Dy (Δt) = 0","Rearrange to solve for Dy: Dy = (sin 50°) (Δm/Δt)V - C","Substitute dm/dt for Δm/Δt: Dy = 0.76604 (dm/dt)V - C","Plug in the given values: Dy = (0.76604)(21.667 kg/s)(20 m/s) - 161.7 N","Calculate Dy = 170.2 N"],"final_answer":"Dx = 154.8 N, Dy = 170.2 N","page_num":888},"14.64":{"problem_text":"Knowing that the blade AB of Sample Problem 14.7 is in the shape of an arc of circle, show that the resultant force F exerted by the blade on the stream is applied at the midpoint C of the arc AB. (Hint: First show that the line of action of F must pass through the center O of the circle.)","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["Assume u_A = u_B = u.","Apply the principle of impulse and momentum.","Take moments about O(+) : R(Δm)u_A k + r_C x F(Δt) = R(Δm)u_B k.","Simplify the moments equation: r_C x F(Δt) = R(Δm)(u_B - u_A)k = 0.","From the moment equation, conclude that the line of action of F passes through Point O.","Consider components in the x-direction (+→): (Δm)u_A + F(Δt) sin α = (Δm)u_B cos θ.","Simplify to get Equation (1): F sin α = (Δm/Δt) * u(1 - cos θ).","Consider components in the y-direction (+↑): 0 + F(Δt) cos α = (Δm)u sin θ.","Simplify to get Equation (2): F cos α = (Δm/Δt) * u sin θ.","Divide Equation (2) by Equation (1): tan α = (u sin θ) / (u(1 - cos θ)) = sin θ / (1 - cos θ).","Use trigonometric identities: sin θ = 2 sin(θ/2) cos(θ/2) and 1 - cos θ = 2 sin²(θ/2).","Simplify tan α = (2 sin(θ/2) cos(θ/2)) / (2 sin²(θ/2)) = cos(θ/2) / sin(θ/2) = cot(θ/2). This step in the original solution has an error as it simplifies to tan(θ/2) instead of cot(θ/2). Let's re-evaluate the division in the provided solution steps.","Re-evaluating the provided solution's division: tan α = (1 - cos θ) / sin θ.  This is based on the provided solution. Let's use the trigonometric identities as they are used in the provided solution: (1 - cos θ) / sin θ = (2 sin²(θ/2)) / (2 sin(θ/2) cos(θ/2)) = tan(θ/2).","Therefore, α = θ/2.","Conclude that Point C lies at the midpoint of arc AB because α is half the angle θ of the arc from point A to B."],"final_answer":"α = θ/2, indicating C is the midpoint of arc AB.","page_num":889},"14.65":{"problem_text":"The stream of water shown flows at a rate of 150 gal/min and moves with a velocity of magnitude 60 ft/s at both A and B. The vane is supported by a pin and bracket at C and by a load cell at D which can exert only a horizontal force. Neglecting the weight of the vane, determine the components of the reactions at C and D (1 ft³ = 7.48 gal).","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["Calculate the mass flow rate (dm/dt) using the given fluid properties and flow rate, converting units appropriately.","Identify the velocity vectors at points A and B, including their magnitudes and directions.","Apply the impulse-momentum principle. First, sum the moments about point C to determine the force D. This involves considering the change in momentum due to the fluid flow and the moment arm for each force.","Use the calculated force D to find the x-component of the reaction at C (Cx) by summing x-components of forces and momentum changes.","Determine the y-component of the reaction at C (Cy) by summing y-components of forces and momentum changes."],"final_answer":"Dx = 76.5 lb, Dy = 0, Cx = -46.7 lb, Cy = 63.8 lb","page_num":890},"14.66":{"problem_text":"The nozzle shown discharges water at the rate of 200 gal/min. Knowing that at both B and C the stream of water moves with a velocity of magnitude 100 ft/s, and neglecting the weight of the vane, determine the force-couple system which must be applied at A to hold the vane in place (1 ft³ = 7.48 gal).","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["Calculate the flow rate Q from gal/min to ft³/s using the given conversion factor (1 ft³ = 7.48 gal) and (60 s/min): \nQ = (200 gal/min) / ((7.48 gal/ft³)(60 s/min)) ≈ 0.44563 ft³/s","Calculate the mass flow rate dm/dt using the formula dm/dt = (γQ)/g, where γ is the specific weight of water (62.4 lb/ft³) and g is the acceleration due to gravity (32.2 ft/s²): \ndm/dt = (62.4 lb/ft³)(0.44563 ft³/s) / (32.2 ft/s²) ≈ 0.8636 lb·s/ft","Define the velocities at point B and C:\nv_B = (100 ft/s)j\nv_C = (100 ft/s)(sin 40°i + cos 40°j)","Apply the impulse-momentum principle:","For the x-components:\n0 + A_x(Δt) = (Δm)(100 sin 40°)\nA_x = (Δm/Δt)(100 sin 40°)\nA_x = (0.8636)(100 sin 40°) ≈ 55.5 lb","For the y-components:\n(Δm)(100) + A_y(Δt) = (Δm)(100 cos 40°)\nA_y = (Δm/Δt)(100 cos 40° - 100)\nA_y = (0.8636)(100)(cos 40° - 1) ≈ -20.2 lb"],"final_answer":"A_x = 55.5 lb, A_y = -20.2 lb (which means 20.2 lb downwards).","page_num":891},"14.67":{"problem_text":"PROBLEM 14.67 (Continued)","method":"f-ma","steps":["Identify x-components: (Δm)v + Rx(Δt) = -(Δm)v sin 50°","Derive the equation for Rx: Rx = -(Δm)/Δt * v(1 + sin 50°)","Substitute given values into the Rx equation: Rx = -(0.36)(61.058)(1 + sin 50°)","Calculate Rx: Rx = -38.82 N","Identify y-components: 0 + Ry(Δt) - W(Δt) = -(Δm)v cos 50°","Derive the equation for Ry: Ry = W + (Δm)/Δt * v cos 50°","Substitute given values into the Ry equation: Ry = (6)(9.81) - (0.36)(61.058)cos 50°","Calculate Ry: Ry = 44.73 N","Calculate the magnitude of the resultant force R using the Pythagorean theorem: R = sqrt((38.82)^2 + (44.73)^2)","Calculate the magnitude R: R = 59.2 N","Calculate the angle α using the tangent function: tan α = 44.73 / 38.82","Calculate α: α = 49.0°"],"final_answer":"R = 59.2 N at an angle of 49.0°","page_num":894},"14.68":{"problem_text":"Coal is being discharged from a first conveyor belt at the rate of 120 kg/s. It is received at A by a second belt which discharges it again at B. Knowing that v₁ =3 m/s and v₂ = 4.25 m/s and that the second belt assembly and the coal it supports have a total mass of 472 kg, determine the components of the reactions at C and D.","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["Calculate the velocity before impact at A: (v_A)_x = v₁ = 3 m/s.","Calculate the y-component of the velocity at A using energy conservation: (v_A)_y² = 2g(Δy) = (2)(9.8)(0.545) = 10.685 m²/s², which gives (v_A)_y = 3.268 m/s.","Determine the slope of the belt: tan θ = (2.4 - 1.2) / 2.25, so θ = 28.07°.","Express the velocity of coal leaving at B: v₂ = 4.25 (cos θ i + sin θ j).","Apply the impulse-momentum principle for x-components: (Δm)(v_A)_x + C_x(Δt) = (Δm)v₂ cos θ. This leads to C_x = (Δm/Δt) [v₂ cos θ − (v_A)_x] = (120) (4.25 cos 28.07° - 3) = 90.0 N.","Apply the impulse-momentum principle for moments about C: (Δm) [-1.2(v_A)_x - 0.75(v_A)_y] + 3.00D(Δt) - 1.8W(Δt) = (Δm) [-2.4 v₂ cos θ + 3v₂ sin θ].","Substitute values and simplify: (Δm) [-(1.2)(3) - (0.75)(3.268)] + 3D - (1.8)(472)(9.8) = (Δm) [-(2.4)(4.25 cos θ) + (3)(4.25 sin θ)].","Rearrange and solve for D: D = 2775 + 1.0168 (dm/dt) = 2775 + (1.0168)(120) = 2897 N."],"final_answer":"C_x = 90.0 N, D = 2897 N","page_num":895},"14.69":{"problem_text":"While cruising in level flight at a speed of 900 km/h, a jet plane scoops in air at the rate of 90 kg/s and discharges it with a velocity of 660 m/s relative to the airplane. Determine the total drag due to air friction on the airplane.","method":"f-ma","steps":["Given flight speed v = 900 km/h. Convert to m/s: 900 km/h = 900 * 1000 m / 3600 s = 250 m/s.","Given mass flow rate dm/dt = 90 kg/s.","Given relative exhaust velocity u = 660 m/s.","For a frame of reference moving with the plane, the free stream velocity v is the air speed.","The drag force D is given by the momentum principle for a system with changing mass: D = (dm/dt) * (u - v) or D = (dm/dt) * (v - u). Considering drag as a resistive force, D = (dm/dt) * (relative exhaust velocity - free stream velocity). In the provided solution, it appears to be D = (dm/dt) * (u_relative_to_plane - v_plane_speed_relative_to_air), where (u_relative_to_plane - v_plane_speed_relative_to_air) represents the relative velocity of the exhaust with respect to the free stream entering the engine. However, based on the calculation, it's (relative exhaust velocity - flight speed) which implies (exhaust_speed_relative_to_plane - air_speed_relative_to_plane).","Substitute the values into the formula: D = (90 kg/s) * (660 m/s - 250 m/s).","Calculate the difference in velocities: 660 - 250 = 410 m/s.","Calculate D: D = 90 * 410 = 36,900 N."],"final_answer":"D = 36.9 kN","page_num":897},"14.70":{"problem_text":"The total drag due to air friction on a jet airplane cruising in level flight at a speed of 570 mi/h is 7500 lb. Knowing that the exhaust velocity is 1800 ft/s relative to the airplane, determine the rate in lb/s at which the air must pass through the engine.","method":"f-ma","steps":["First, convert the flight speed from mi/h to ft/s: v = 570 mi/h = 836 ft/s.","Apply the thrust equation, considering a frame of reference moving with the plane, where D is drag force, dm/dt is the mass flow rate of air, u is the relative exhaust velocity, and v is the free stream velocity (equal to the air speed): ΣF = D = - (dm/dt)(u - v). Alternatively, D = (dm/dt)(u - v) considering the direction.","Solve for the mass flow rate of air (dm/dt) using the given values for drag (D = 7500 lb), relative exhaust velocity (u = 1800 ft/s), and flight speed (v = 836 ft/s): dm/dt = D / (u - v) = 7500 / (1800 - 836) = 7.78 slugs/s.","Calculate the rate at which the air must pass through the engine in lb/s (dW/dt). This is equivalent to dm/dt * g, where g is the acceleration due to gravity (32.2 ft/s²). So, dW/dt = g * (dm/dt) = (32.2)(7.78).","Calculate the final value of dW/dt: dW/dt = 250.756 lb/s ≈ 251 lb/s."],"final_answer":"dW/dt = 251 lb/s","page_num":898},"14.71":{"problem_text":"The jet engine shown scoops in air at A at a rate of 200 lb/s and discharges it at B with a velocity of 2000 ft/s relative to the airplane. Determine the magnitude and line of action of the propulsive thrust developed by the engine when the speed of the airplane is (a) 300 mi/h, (b) 600 mi/h.","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["Use a frame of reference moving with the plane. Apply the impulse-momentum principle. Let F be the force that the plane exerts on the air.","Formulate the x-components equation: (Δm)u_A + F(Δt) = (Δm)u_B.","Derive F = (dm/dt)(u_B - u_A) from the x-components equation.","Formulate the moments about B equation: -e(Δm)u_A + M_B(Δt) = 0.","Derive M_B = e(dm/dt)u_A from the moments about B equation.","Let d be the distance that the line of action is below B. Formulate Fd = M_B.","Derive d = M_B / F = eu_A / (u_B - u_A).","Convert given data: dm/dt = 200 lb/s = 200/32.2 slugs/s = 6.2112 slugs/s, u_B = 2000 ft/s, e = 12 ft.","For part (a), airplane speed u_A = 300 mi/h = 440 ft/s.","Calculate F from Eq. (1): F = (6.2112)(2000 - 440).","Calculate d from Eq. (3): d = (12)(440) / (2000 - 440).","For part (b), airplane speed u_A = 600 mi/h = 880 ft/s.","Calculate F from Eq. (1): F = (6.2112)(2000 - 880).","Calculate d from Eq. (3): d = (12)(880) / (2000 - 880)."],"final_answer":"(a) F = 9690 lb, d = 3.38 ft (b) F = 6960 lb, d = 9.43 ft","page_num":899},"14.73":{"problem_text":"A floor fan designed to deliver air at a maximum velocity of 6 m/s in a 400-mm-diameter slipstream is supported by a 200-mm-diameter circular base plate. Knowing that the total weight of the assembly is 60 N and that its center of gravity is located directly above the center of the base plate, determine the maximum height h at which the fan may be operated if it is not to tip over. Assume ρ=1.21 kg/m³ for air and neglect the approach velocity of the air.","method":"otro","steps":["Calculate the mass flow rate (dm/dt) in the airstream: mass = density × volume = density × area × length, so Δm = ρA(Δl) = ρAv(Δt). Therefore, dm/dt = ρAv.","Calculate the thrust on the airstream (F) using the momentum principle: F = dm/dt * (v_B - v_A), where v_B is the velocity just downstream of the fan and v_A is the velocity upstream. Assuming v_A is negligible, F = (ρAv)v = ρ(π/4 D²)v².","Substitute the given values: ρ = 1.21 kg/m³, D = 400 mm = 0.400 m, v = 6 m/s. Calculate F: F = (1.21 kg/m³) * (π/4) * (0.400 m)² * (6 m/s)² = 5.474 N.","The force on the fan (F') is equal and opposite to the thrust F: F' = -F = 5.474 N.","Determine the maximum height h at which the fan may be operated if it is not to tip over. This requires balancing torques about point E, which is the edge of the base plate. The distance from the center to the edge of the base plate is e = d/2 = 200 mm / 2 = 100 mm = 0.1 m.","Sum of moments about point E is zero (ΣM_E = 0): F'h - We = 0.","Solve for h: h = We / F'.","Substitute the values: W = 60 N, e = 0.1 m, F' = 5.474 N. Calculate h: h = (60 N)(0.1 m) / 5.474 N.","Calculate the final value of h: h = 1.096 m."],"final_answer":"h = 1.096 m","page_num":901},"14.74":{"problem_text":"The helicopter shown can produce a maximum downward air speed of 80 ft/s in a 30-ft-diameter slipstream. Knowing that the weight of the helicopter and its crew is 3500 lb and assuming y=0.076 lb/ft³ for air, determine the maximum load that the helicopter can lift while hovering in midair.","method":"otro","steps":["The thrust is given by the formula F = dm/dt * (v_B - v_A).","Calculate dm/dt from mass = density × volume = density × area × length.","Δm = ρA_B(Δl) = ρA_Bv_B(Δt) so Δm/Δt = ρA_Bv_B = (γ/g)A_Bv_B. Therefore, dm/dt = (γ/g)A_Bv_B.","Given that v_A ≈ 0 well above the blade, the thrust simplifies to F = (γ/g)A_Bv_B².","Substitute the given values: γ = 0.076 lb/ft³, g = 32.2 ft/s², diameter = 30 ft, v_B = 80 ft/s.","Calculate the area A_B = (π/4) * (30 ft)².","F = (0.076 lb/ft³ / 32.2 ft/s²) * (π/4) * (30 ft)² * (80 ft/s)² = 10,678 lb.","Apply Newtons second law for static equilibrium: ΣF_y = F - W_H - W_P = 0.","Given the weight of the helicopter W_H = 3500 lb.","Solve for the payload weight W_P = F - W_H.","W_P = 10,678 lb - 3500 lb = 7178 lb."],"final_answer":"W = 7180 lb","page_num":902},"14.75":{"problem_text":"A jet airliner is cruising at a speed of 600 mi/h with each of its three engines discharging air with a velocity of 2000 ft/s relative to the plane. Determine the speed of the airliner after it has lost the use of (a) one of its engines, (b) two of its engines. Assume that the drag due to air friction is proportional to the square of the speed and that the remaining engines keep operating at the same rate.","method":"f-ma","steps":["Identify the given variables: v is the airliner speed, u is the discharge relative velocity (u = 2000 ft/s).","State the thrust formula for one engine: F = (dm/dt)(u - v).","State the drag formula: D = kv^2.","For three engines working, the cruising speed is v_0 = 600 mi/h = 880 ft/s.","Set the thrust equal to the drag for three engines: 3F - D = 3(dm/dt)(u - v_0) - kv_0^2 = 0.","Solve for (dm/dt) in terms of k and known values: (dm/dt) = (kv_0^2) / (3(u - v_0)) = (k(880)^2) / (3(2000 - 880)) = 230.48k.","For part (a), one engine fails, so two engines are working. Let the new cruising speed be v_1.","Set the thrust for two engines equal to the drag: 2F - D = 2(dm/dt)(u - v_1) - kv_1^2 = 0.","Substitute the expression for (dm/dt): 2(230.48k)(2000 - v_1) - kv_1^2 = 0.","Divide by k and simplify to form a quadratic equation: v_1^2 + 460.96v_1 - 921.92 x 10^3 = 0.","Solve the quadratic equation for v_1: v_1 = 756.96 ft/s.","Convert v_1 to mi/h: v_1 = 516 mi/h.","For part (b), two engines fail, so one engine is working. Let the new cruising speed be v_2.","Set the thrust for one engine equal to the drag: F - D = (dm/dt)(u - v_2) - kv_2^2 = 0.","Substitute the expression for (dm/dt): (230.48k)(2000 - v_2) - kv_2^2 = 0.","Divide by k and simplify to form a quadratic equation: v_2^2 + 230.48v_2 - 460.96 x 10^3 = 0.","Solve the quadratic equation for v_2: v_2 = 573.41 ft/s.","Convert v_2 to mi/h: v_2 = 391 mi/h."],"final_answer":"(a) v_1 = 516 mi/h, (b) v_2 = 391 mi/h","page_num":903},"14.76":{"problem_text":"A 16-Mg jet airplane maintains a constant speed of 774 km/h while climbing at an angle α=18°. The airplane scoops in air at a rate of 300 kg/s and discharges it with a velocity of 665 m/s relative to the airplane. If the pilot changes to a horizontal flight while maintaining the same engine setting, determine (a) the initial acceleration of the plane, (b) the maximum horizontal speed that will be attained. Assume that the drag due to air friction is proportional to the square of the speed.","method":"f-ma","steps":["Calculate the propulsive force using velocities relative to the airplane: F = (dm/dt)(vB - vA).","Convert vA from km/h to m/s: vA = 774 km/h = 215 m/s.","Substitute given values into the propulsive force equation: F = (300 kg/s)(665 m/s - 215 m/s) = 135,000 N.","Since there is no acceleration while climbing, forces are in equilibrium: ΣFy' = 0 (perpendicular to motion) and ΣFx' = 0 (along motion).","From equilibrium along the motion (at 18°): F - D - mg sin α = 0, where m is the mass of the airplane (16 Mg = 16,000 kg).","Calculate the drag force D: D = F - mg sin α = 135,000 N - (16,000 kg)(9.8 m/s²)(sin 18°) = 135,000 N - 48,454 N = 86,546 N.","For part (a), determine the initial acceleration of the airplane in horizontal flight. The propulsive force F remains the same. The drag D also remains the same initially, and the angle α becomes 0 for horizontal flight. The net force is F - D = ma.","Calculate the net force: F - D = 135,000 N - 86,546 N = 48,454 N.","Calculate the initial acceleration: a = (F - D) / m = 48,454 N / 16,000 kg = 3.028 m/s².","Determine the drag force factor k, assuming drag is proportional to the square of the speed (D = kv²). Using the climbing phase data: k = D / vA² = 86,546 N / (215 m/s)² = 1.87228 N·s²/m²."],"final_answer":"a = 3.03 m/s²","page_num":904},"14.77":{"problem_text":"The wind turbine-generator shown has an output-power rating of 5 kW for a wind speed of 30 km/h. For the given wind speed, determine (a) the kinetic energy of the air particles entering the 7.50-m-diameter circle per second, (b) the efficiency of this energy-conversion system. Assume ρ=1.21 kg/m³ for air.","method":"potencia","steps":["Identify the given values: output-power rating = 5 kW, wind speed v = 30 km/h, diameter D = 7.50 m, density of air ρ = 1.21 kg/m³.","Convert the wind speed from km/h to m/s: v = 30 km/h = 30 * (1000 m / 1 km) * (1 h / 3600 s) = 8.333 m/s.","Calculate the area A of the circle swept by the turbine blades: A = π(D/2)² = π(7.50 m / 2)² = π(3.75 m)² = 44.179 m².","For part (a), determine the kinetic energy of the air particles entering the circle per second, which represents the rate of kinetic energy (power). The formula for the kinetic energy rate (power) of the air is P_air = (1/2) * (dm/dt) * v², where dm/dt is the mass flow rate. The mass flow rate dm/dt can be expressed as ρ * Q = ρ * A * v.","Substitute dm/dt into the power equation: P_air = (1/2) * ρ * A * v * v² = (1/2) * ρ * A * v³.","Calculate P_air using the given values: P_air = (1/2) * (1.21 kg/m³) * (44.179 m²) * (8.333 m/s)³.","P_air = (1/2) * (1.21 kg/m³) * (π/4) * (7.50 m)² * (30 * 10³/ (3.6 * 10³ s))³.","P_air = 15474.9 W = 15.4749 kJ/s.","For part (b), calculate the efficiency η of the energy-conversion system. Efficiency is defined as the ratio of the output power to the input power. Here, the output power is the turbine rated power, and the input power is the kinetic energy of the air per second (P_air).","Given output power P_out = 5 kW = 5000 W.","Calculate η = P_out / P_air = 5000 W / 15474.9 W.","η = 0.32309 ≈ 0.323."],"final_answer":"(a) dT/dt = 15.47 kJ/s, (b) η = 0.323","page_num":906},"14.79":{"problem_text":"While cruising in level flight at a speed of 570 mi/h, a jet airplane scoops in air at a rate of 240 lb/s and discharges it with a velocity of 2200 ft/s relative to the airplane. Determine (a) the power actually used to propel the airplane, (b) the total power developed by the engine, (c) the mechanical efficiency of the airplane.","method":"potencia","steps":["Identify given data: Rate of air scooped in = 240 lb/s, velocity of discharged air relative to airplane = u = 2200 ft/s, speed of airplane = v = 570 mi/h.","Convert given values to consistent units: dm/dt = (240 lb/s) / (32.2 ft/s²) = 7.4534 slugs/s. Convert airplane speed from mi/h to ft/s: v = 570 mi/h * (5280 ft/1 mi) * (1 h/3600 s) = 836 ft/s.","Calculate the thrust force F developed by the engine using the momentum equation: F = (dm/dt)(u - v) = (7.4534 slugs/s)(2200 ft/s - 836 ft/s) = 10,166 lb.","(a) Calculate the power actually used to propel the airplane (Propulsion Power, P1): P1 = Fv = (10,166 lb)(836 ft/s) = 8.499 x 10^6 ft·lb/s.","Convert P1 to horsepower: P1_hp = (8.499 x 10^6 ft·lb/s) / (550 ft·lb/s per hp) = 15,450 hp.","Calculate the power corresponding to the kinetic energy of the exhaust (P2): P2 = (1/2)(dm/dt)(u - v)^2 = (1/2)(7.4534 slugs/s)(2200 ft/s - 836 ft/s)^2 = 6.934 x 10^6 ft·lb/s.","(b) Calculate the total power developed by the engine (P): P = P1 + P2 = 8.499 x 10^6 ft·lb/s + 6.934 x 10^6 ft·lb/s = 15.433 x 10^6 ft·lb/s.","Convert P to horsepower: P_hp = (15.433 x 10^6 ft·lb/s) / (550 ft·lb/s per hp) = 28,060 hp.","(c) Calculate the mechanical efficiency of the airplane (η): η = P1 / P = (8.499 x 10^6 ft·lb/s) / (15.433 x 10^6 ft·lb/s) = 0.551."],"final_answer":"a) Propulsion power = 15,450 hp, b) Total power = 28,060 hp, c) Mechanical efficiency = 0.551","page_num":908},"14.80":{"problem_text":"The propeller of a small airplane has a 6-ft-diameter slipstream and produces a thrust of 800 lb when the airplane is at fix on the ground. Assuming γ = 0.076 lb/ft³ for air, determine (a) the speed of the air in the slipstream, (b) the volume of air passing through the propeller per second, (c) the kinetic energy imparted per second to the air in the slipstream.","method":"otro","steps":["Calculation of mass flow rate: dm/dt = ρAv, where ρ = γ/g.","For part (a), Thrust = (dm/dt)(vb - va), where va is negligible. So, Thrust = (ρAv)v. We have Thrust = 800 lb, diameter D = 6 ft, so area A = (π/4)D². Given γ = 0.076 lb/ft³ and g = 32.2 ft/s². Substitute these values into the thrust equation to solve for v.","800 = (0.076/32.2) * (π/4)(6)² * v².","This simplifies to 800 = 0.066734v².","Solving for v: v = √(800/0.066734) = 109.489 ft/s.","For part (b), the volume of air passing through the propeller per second is Q = Av.","Q = (π/4)D² * v = (π/4)(6)² * 109.489.","Q = 3100 ft³/s.","For part (c), the kinetic energy imparted per second is dT/dt. The kinetic energy of a mass Δm moving at velocity v is (1/2)Δmv². So, dT/dt = (1/2)(dm/dt)v².","dT/dt = (1/2) * (ρAv) * v² = (1/2) * ρA * v³.","Substitute ρ, A, and v: dT/dt = (1/2) * (γ/g) * (π/4)D² * v³.","dT/dt = (1/2) * (0.076/32.2) * (π/4)(6)² * (109.489)³.","dT/dt = 43,796 ft·lb/s."],"final_answer":"a) v = 109.5 ft/s, b) Q = 3100 ft³/s, c) dT/dt = 43,800 ft·lb/s","page_num":909},"14.81":{"problem_text":"In a Pelton-wheel turbine, a stream of water is deflected by a series of blades so that the rate at which water is deflected by the blades is equal to the rate at which water issues from the nozzle (Δm/Δt = Aρν_A). Using the same notation as in Sample Problem 14.7, (a) determine the velocity V of the blades for which maximum power is developed, (b) derive an expression for the maximum power, (c) derive an expression for the mechanical efficiency.","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["Identify the relative velocity of the stream to the blade as u = (v - V).","Define the mass flow rate as Δm/Δt = ρAv_A.","Apply the principle of impulse and momentum in the tangential direction: (Δm)u - F_t(Δt) = (Δm)u cos θ. From this, derive F_t = (Δm/Δt)u(1 - cos θ) = ρAv_A(v_A - V)(1 - cos θ).","State that the tangential force on the blade is F_t to the right, by Newton's third law.","Define the output power as P_out = F_tV = ρAv_A(v_A - V)V(1 - cos θ).","To find the velocity V for maximum power output (part a), differentiate P_out with respect to V and set it to zero: dP_out/dV = ρAv_A(v_A - 2V)(1 - cos θ) = 0. Solve for V to get v_A = (1/2)V.","To derive the expression for maximum power (part b), substitute V = (1/2)v_A into the P_out expression: (P_out)_max = ρAv_A(v_A - (1/2)v_A)(1/2)v_A(1 - cos θ) = (1/4)ρAv_A^3(1 - cos θ)."],"final_answer":"(a) V = (1/2)v_A, (b) (P_out)_max = (1/4)ρAv_A^3(1 - cos θ)","page_num":910},"14.82":{"problem_text":"A circular reentrant orifice (also called Borda's mouthpiece) of diameter D is placed at a depth h below the surface of a tank. Knowing that the speed of the issuing stream is v=√2gh and assuming that the speed of approach v is zero, show that the diameter of the stream is d=D/√2. (Hint: Consider the section of water indicated, and note that P is equal to the pressure at a depth h multiplied by the area of the orifice).","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["From hydrostatics, the pressure at Section 1 is p₁ = ρh = ρgh.","The pressure at Section 2 is p₂ = 0.","Calculate the mass flow rate using Section 2: mass = density × volume = density × area × length. Δm = ρA₂(Δl) = ρA₂v(Δt). So, dm/dt = Δm/Δt = ρA₂v.","Apply the impulse-momentum principle to fluid between Sections 1 and 2: (Δm)v₁ + p₁A₁(Δt) = (Δm)v + (Δm)v₂. This simplifies to dm/dt * v₁ + p₁A₁ = dm/dt * v. So, p₁A₁ = dm/dt * (v - v₁). Substituting dm/dt = ρA₂v, we get p₁A₁ = ρA₂v(v - v₁).","Given that v₁ is negligible, the equation becomes p₁A₁ = ρA₂v². Substituting p₁ = ρgh and v = √2gh, we get ρghA₁ = ρA₂(2gh).","This simplifies to A₁ = 2A₂.","Substituting the area formulas, π/4 D² = 2(π/4 d²).","Solving for d, we get d = D/√2."],"final_answer":"d = D/√2","page_num":912},"14.83":{"problem_text":"The depth of water flowing in a rectangular channel of width b at a speed v₁ and a depth d₁ increases to a depth d₂ at a hydraulic jump. Express the rate of flow Q in terms of b, d₁, and d₂.","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["Define mass flow rate as mass = density × volume = density × area × length. Therefore, Δm = ρbd(Δl) = ρbdv(Δt).","Calculate the mass flow rate dm/dt = Δm/Δt = ρbdv. From this, Q = (1/ρ) dm/dt = bdv.","Apply the Continuity of flow principle: Q₁ = Q₂ = Q. From the definition of flow rate, v₁ = Q/(bd₁) and v₂ = Q/(bd₂).","Calculate the resultant pressure forces. The pressure at section 1 is p₁ = γd₁ and at section 2 is p₂ = γd₂. The forces are F₁ = (1/2)p₁bd₁ = (1/2)γbd₁² and F₂ = (1/2)p₂bd₂ = (1/2)γbd₂².","Apply the impulse-momentum principle to the water between Sections 1 and 2: (Δm)v₁ + F₁(Δt) - F₂(Δt) = (Δm)v₂. This can be rewritten as (Δm/Δt)(v₁ - v₂) = F₂ - F₁.","Substitute the expressions for Δm/Δt, v₁, v₂, F₁, and F₂ into the impulse-momentum equation: ρQ(Q/(bd₁) - Q/(bd₂)) = (1/2)γbd₂² - (1/2)γbd₁².","Simplify the equation: ρQ²((d₂ - d₁)/(bd₁d₂)) = (1/2)γb(d₂² - d₁²). Since d₂² - d₁² = (d₂ - d₁)(d₂ + d₁), the equation becomes ρQ²(d₂ - d₁)/(bd₁d₂) = (1/2)γb(d₂ - d₁)(d₂ + d₁).","Cancel (d₂ - d₁) (assuming d₁ ≠ d₂) and rearrange to solve for Q²: ρQ²/(bd₁d₂) = (1/2)γb(d₁ + d₂).","Knowing that γ = ρg, substitute γ into the equation: ρQ²/(bd₁d₂) = (1/2)ρgb(d₁ + d₂).","Solve for Q: Q² = (1/2)gb²d₁d₂(d₁ + d₂).","Take the square root to find Q: Q = b * sqrt( (1/2)gd₁d₂(d₁ + d₂) )."],"final_answer":"Q = b \\sqrt{\\frac{1}{2}gd_1 d_2(d_1+d_2)}","page_num":913},"14.84":{"problem_text":"Determine the rate of flow in the channel of Problem 14.83, knowing that b = 12 ft, d₁ =4 ft, and d₂ = 5 ft. PROBLEM 14.83 The depth of water flowing in a rectangular channel of width b at a speed v₁ and a depth d₁ increases to a depth d₂ at a hydraulic jump. Express the rate of flow Q in terms of b, d₁, and d₂.","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["Define mass flow rate: mass = density × volume = density × area × length. Δm = pbd(Δl) = pbdv(Δt). Therefore, dm/dt = Δm/Δt = pbdv. And Q = (1/p)dm/dt = bdv.","Apply continuity of flow: Q₁ = Q₂ = Q. From the mass flow rate definition, v₁ = Q/(bd₁) and v₂ = Q/(bd₂).","Identify resultant pressure forces: p₁ = γd₁ and p₂ = γd₂. F₁ = (1/2)p₁bd₁ = (1/2)γbd₁². F₂ = (1/2)p₂bd₂ = (1/2)γbd₂².","Apply the impulse-momentum principle to water between Sections 1 and 2: (Δm)v₁ + F₁(Δt) - F₂(Δt) = (Δm)v₂.","Rearrange the impulse-momentum equation: Δm(v₁ - v₂) = F₂ - F₁.","Divide by Δt and substitute for dm/dt and Q: (dm/dt)(v₁ - v₂) = F₂ - F₁.","Substitute Q into the equation: pQ(Q/(bd₁) - Q/(bd₂)) = F₂ - F₁.","Substitute expressions for F₁ and F₂: pQ²(1/(bd₁) - 1/(bd₂)) = (1/2)γbd₂² - (1/2)γbd₁².","Simplify and solve for Q²: pQ²(d₂ - d₁)/(bd₁d₂) = (1/2)γb(d₂² - d₁²). Since γ = pg, then pQ²(d₂ - d₁)/(bd₁d₂) = (1/2)pgb(d₂ - d₁)(d₂ + d₁).","Solve for Q²: Q² = (1/2)gb²d₁d₂(d₂ + d₁).","Substitute given values: b = 12 ft, d₁ = 4 ft, d₂ = 5 ft. And g = 32.2 ft/s².","Calculate Q² = (1/2)(32.2)(12)²(4)(5)(5+4) = (1/2)(32.2)(144)(20)(9) = 417380.0 ft⁶/s².","Calculate Q = √417380.0 = 646.05 ft³/s."],"final_answer":"Q = 646 ft³/s","page_num":914},"14.85":{"problem_text":"Gravel falls with practically zero velocity onto a conveyor belt at the constant rate q=dm/dt.\n(a) Determine the magnitude of the force P required to maintain a constant belt speed v.\n(b) Show that the kinetic energy acquired by the gravel in a given time interval is equal to half the work done in that interval by the force P.\nExplain what happens to the other half of the work done by P.","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["(a) We apply the impulse-momentum principle to the gravel on the belt and to the mass Δm of gravel hitting and leaving belt in interval Δt: x comp.: mv + PΔt = mv + (Δm)v","From the impulse-momentum principle: P = (Δm/Δt)v = qv.","(b) Kinetic energy acquired for unit time: ΔT = (1/2)(Δm)v²","ΔT/Δt = (1/2)(Δm/Δt)v² = (1/2)qv² (1)","Work done per unit time: ΔU/Δt = PΔx/Δt = Pv","Recalling the result of Part a (P = qv), we substitute P in the work done equation: ΔU/Δt = (qv)v = qv² (2)","Comparing Eqs. (1) and (2), we conclude that ΔT/Δt = (1/2)ΔU/Δt.","The other half of the work of P is dissipated into heat by friction as the gravel slips on the belt before reaching the speed v."],"final_answer":"P = qv; The kinetic energy acquired by the gravel is half the work done by P. The other half of the work is dissipated as heat due to friction.","page_num":916},"14.86":{"problem_text":"A chain of length l and mass m falls through a small hole in a plate. Initially, when y is very small, the chain is at rest. In each case shown, determine (a) the acceleration of the first link A as a function of y, (b) the velocity of the chain as the last link passes through the hole. In Case 1, assume that the individual links are at rest until they fall through the hole; in Case 2, assume that at any instant all links have the same speed. Ignore the effect of friction.","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["Let ρ be the mass per unit length of chain. Assume that the weight of any chain above the hole is supported by the floor. It and the corresponding upward reaction of the floor are not shown in the diagrams.","Case 1. Apply the impulse-momentum principle to the entire chain: ρyv + ρgΔt = ρ(y+Δy)(v+Δv).","Expand the right side: ρyv + ρgΔt = ρyv + ρ(Δy)v + ρy(Δv) + ρ(Δy)(Δv).","Simplify and divide by Δt: ρg = ρ(Δy/Δt)v + ρy(Δv/Δt) + ρ(Δy/Δt)(Δv).","Let Δt → 0. Since v = dy/dt and dv/dt = a, and (Δy/Δt)(Δv) also approaches zero, the equation becomes: ρg = ρv(dy/dt) + ρy(dv/dt).","Substitute v = dy/dt: ρg = ρv² + ρy(dv/dt). This can be rewritten as ρg = ρ(d/dt)(yv).","Multiply both sides by yv: ρgyv = ρyv(d/dt)(yv).","Let v = dy/dt on the left hand side: ρgy²(dy/dt) = ρyv(d/dt)(yv). This step seems to be a mistake in the provided solution steps; the previous step 'ρg = ρ(d/dt)(yv)' can be written as ρgy = ρ(d/dt)(yv) and seems to relate to the next integration step.","The step 'Let v = dy/dt on left hand side. ρgy²(dy/dt) = ρyv(d/dt)(yv)' is incorrect or misapplied. The previous step was ρgy = ρ(d/dt)(yv).","Integrating the correct form: ∫pg y dy = ∫ρ (d/dt)(yv) dt. This is equivalent to ∫pg y dy = ρ ∫d(yv).","The solution shows: ∫ρg y² dy = ρ∫d(yv). This is if we multiply ρgy = ρ(d/dt)(yv) by y and integrate with respect to y, which seems incorrect contextually. Let's follow the provided solution for this step: (1/3)ρgy³ = (1/2)ρ(yv)². This implies that the term to integrate was ρgy given ρ(d/dt)(yv). If we integrate (ρg = ρ d/dt (yv)) with respect to time, it would be ρgt = ρyv. This solution path is different.","Let's re-evaluate from ρgy = ρd/dt(yv). This implies g y dt = d(yv). Integrating is ∫g y dt = ∫d(yv). This doesn't seem to lead to the given result.","Let's follow the solution as provided: ρgy = ρ(d/dt)(yv). This can be written as gy = d(yv)/dt. When integrated to get the velocity squared, it should be derived from energy or similar methods. The solution provides (1/3)ρgy³ = (1/2)ρ(yv)².","From (1/3)ρgy³ = (1/2)ρ(yv)², we simplify to: (2/3)ρgy³ = ρy²v² => v² = (2/3)gy. Or v = √(2gy/3).","Differentiate with respect to time to find acceleration: 2v(dv/dt) = (2/3)g(dy/dt).","Since dy/dt = v, we have 2v(dv/dt) = (2/3)gv.","Therefore, dv/dt = (1/3)g. This is the acceleration of the first link A for Case 1."],"final_answer":"a = g/3","page_num":917},"14.87":{"problem_text":"A chain of length l and mass m lies in a pile on the floor. If its end A is raised vertically at a constant speed v, express in terms of the length y of chain which is off the floor at any given instant (a) the magnitude of the force P applied at A, (b) the reaction of the floor.","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["Let ρ be the mass per unit length of chain.","Apply the impulse-momentum principle to the entire chain.","The impulse-momentum equation is ρyv + P(Δt) + R(Δt) - ρgL(Δt) = ρ(y + Δy)v.","Rearrange for PΔt: PΔt = ρ(Δy)v + ρgL(Δt) - R(Δt).","Substitute R(Δt) = ρgL(Δt) - ρg(L-y)gΔt.","Simplify to find P in terms of ρ, v, g, y, and Δy/Δt: P = ρ(Δy/Δt)v + ρgL - ρ(L-y)g.","Since Δy/Δt ≈ v, P = ρv² + ρgy.","Express P in terms of m, l, v, and g: P = (m/l)(v² + gy).","For the reaction of the floor, R = ρg(l-y).","Express R in terms of m, l, g, and y: R = mg(1 - y/l)."],"final_answer":"(a) P = (m/l)(v²+gy); (b) R = mg(1-y/l)","page_num":919},"14.88":{"problem_text":"Solve Problem 14.87, assuming that the chain is being lowered to the floor at a constant speed v.","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["Let ρ be the mass per unit length of chain. The force P supports the weight of chain still off the floor.","Therefore, P = ρgy.","Apply the impulse-momentum principle to the entire chain, considering the forces and momentum changes over a time internal Δt.","The initial momentum is -ρyv.","The impulses are P(Δt) (upwards), R(Δt) (upwards, reaction force from the floor), and -pgL(Δt) (downwards, for the whole chain).","The final momentum is -ρg(y + Δy)v.","The impulse-momentum equation is -ρyv + P(Δt) + R(Δt) - ρgL(Δt) = -ρg(y + Δy)v.","Rearranging to solve for R(Δt): R(Δt) = ρgL(Δt) - P(Δt) - ρg(Δy)v.","Substitute P = ρgy: R(Δt) = ρgL(Δt) - ρgy(Δt) - ρg(Δy)v.","Divide by Δt: R = ρgL - ρgy - ρ(Δy/Δt)v.","As Δt approaches 0, Δy/Δt becomes dy/dt.","Since the chain is being lowered, the change in length y over time is negative, so dy/dt = -v.","Substitute dy/dt = -v into the equation for R: R = ρgL - ρgy - ρ(-v)v.","Simplify to get R = ρg(L - y) + ρv².","Recognize that ρ is mass per unit length, so the total mass m = ρL. Therefore, ρ = m/L.","Substitute ρ = m/L into the equation for R: R = (m/L)g(L - y) + (m/L)v².","Factor out m/L: R = (m/L)[g(L - y) + v²]."],"final_answer":"R = (m/L)[g(L - y) + v²]","page_num":920},"14.89":{"problem_text":"A toy car is propelled by water that squirts from an internal tank at a constant 6 ft/s relative to the car. The weight of the empty car is 0.4 lb and it holds 2 lb of water. Neglecting other tangential forces, determine the top speed of the car.","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["Consider a time interval Δt. Let m be the mass of the car plus the water in the tank at the beginning of the interval and (m-Δm) the corresponding mass at the end of the interval. m₀ is the initial value of m. Let v be the velocity of the car. Apply the impulse and momentum principle over the time interval.","Draw free body diagrams for the initial state, impulses, and final state.","Apply the impulse-momentum principle in the horizontal direction: mv + 0 = (Δm)(-U cos 20°) + (m - Δm)(v + Δv).","Simplify the equation to find Δv = U cos 20° (Δm / (m - Δm)).","Replace Δv with differential dv and Δm with differential -dm (where dm is the infinitesimal increase in mass, so a decrease in system mass is represented by a positive dm). Thus, dv = -U cos 20° (dm / m).","Integrate the differential equation for velocity: ∫dv = ∫(-U cos 20° / m) dm.","This yields v = v₀ - U cos 20° ln(m / m₀).","Since v₀ = 0 (the car starts from rest), the equation becomes v = U cos 20° ln(m₀ / m).","The velocity is maximum when the mass m reaches its final value (mf), which is when all the water is expelled.","Calculate the initial mass m₀ and final mass mf. Weight of empty car = 0.4 lb, Weight of water = 2 lb. So m₀ = (0.4 + 2) / g = 2.4 / g and mf = 0.4 / g. The ratio m₀ / mf = (2.4/g) / (0.4/g) = 2.4 / 0.4 = 6.","Substitute the values into the maximum velocity equation: v_max = (6 ft/s) cos 20° ln( (0.4 + 2) / 0.4 ).","Calculate the final value: v_max = (6 ft/s) cos 20° ln(6)."],"final_answer":"v_max = 10.10 ft/s","page_num":921},"14.90":{"problem_text":"A toy car is propelled by water that squirts from an internal tank. The weight of the empty car is 0.4 lb and it holds 2 lb of water. Knowing the top speed of the car is 8 ft/s, determine the relative velocity of the water that is being ejected.","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["Consider a time interval Δt. Let m be the mass of the car plus the water in the tank at the beginning of the interval and (m - Δm) the corresponding mass at the end of the interval. m₀ is the initial value of m. Let v be the velocity of the car. Apply the impulse and momentum principle over the time interval.","Write the horizontal components of the impulse-momentum equation: mv + 0 = (Δm)(-U cos 20°) + (m - Δm)(v + Δv)","Simplify the equation to express Δv: Δv = U cos 20° (Δm / (m - Δm))","Replace Δv with differential dv and Δm with differential -dm, where -dm signifies an infinitesimal increase in m (meaning dm is an infinitesimal decrease). Thus, dv = -U cos 20° (dm / m).","Integrate the differential equation: ∫dv = ∫(-U cos 20° (dm / m)). This yields v = v₀ - U cos 20° ln(m / m₀).","Since the initial velocity v₀ = 0, the equation becomes v = U cos 20° ln(m₀ / m).","The velocity is maximum when all the water is expelled, meaning m = m_f (mass of the empty car).","Substitute the maximum velocity v_max = 8 ft/s and the masses into the equation: 8 ft/s = U cos 20° ln((0.4 + 2) / 0.4)."],"final_answer":"U = 4.75 ft/s","page_num":922},"14.92":{"problem_text":"The main propulsion system of a space shuttle consists of three identical rocket engines which provide a total thrust of 6 MN. Determine the rate at which the hydrogen-oxygen propellant is burned by each of the three engines, knowing that it is ejected with a relative velocity of 3750 m/s.","method":"f-ma","steps":["Calculate the thrust of each engine: P = (1/3) * (6 MN) = 2x10^6 N.","Use Equation (14.44) for thrust: P = (dm/dt) * u, where u is the relative velocity.","Substitute the values: 2x10^6 N = (dm/dt) * (3750 m/s).","Solve for dm/dt: dm/dt = (2x10^6 N) / (3750 m/s)."],"final_answer":"dm/dt = 533 kg/s","page_num":924},"14.93":{"problem_text":"A space vehicle describing a circular orbit at a speed of 24x10³ km/h releases its front end a capsule which has a gross mass of 600 kg, including 400 kg of fuel. If the fuel is consumed at the constant rate of 18 kg/s and ejected with a relative velocity of 3000 m/s, determine (a) the tangential acceleration of the capsule as the engine is fired, (b) the maximum speed attained by the capsule.","method":"f-ma","steps":["Calculate the thrust P using the given rate of fuel consumption and relative velocity: P = |dm/dt * u| = (18 kg/s)(3000 m/s) = 54x10³ N.","Calculate the initial tangential acceleration (a_t)_0 when the engine is fired. This is given by the thrust divided by the initial mass m_0: (a_t)_0 = P/m_0 = (54x10³ N) / (600 kg) = 90 m/s².","For part (b), determine the maximum speed attained by the capsule. This occurs when all the fuel is used up. Using the rocket equation, the change in velocity is given by v₁ = v₀ + u ln(m₀/m₁).","Identify the initial velocity v₀ = 24x10³ km/h. Convert v₀ to m/s: 24x10³ km/h = 24x10³ * (1000 m / 3600 s) = 6.6667x10³ m/s.","Given the relative ejection velocity u = 3000 m/s.","Given the initial mass m₀ = 600 kg.","Calculate the final mass m₁ after 400 kg of fuel is consumed: m₁ = 600 kg - 400 kg = 200 kg.","Substitute these values into the rocket equation: v₁ = 6.6667x10³ m/s + 3000 m/s * ln(600 kg / 200 kg).","Calculate the natural logarithm term: ln(3) = 1.0986.","Calculate v₁: v₁ = 6.6667x10³ + 3000 * 1.0986 = 6.6667x10³ + 3295.8 = 9962.5 m/s.","Convert the final speed v₁ to km/h: v₁ = 9962.5 m/s * (3600 s / 1000 m) = 35865 km/h ≈ 35.9x10³ km/h."],"final_answer":"(a) (a_t)_0 = 90.0 m/s², (b) v₁ = 35.9x10³ km/h","page_num":925},"14.95":{"problem_text":"Data:\nv₁ - v₀ = 8000 ft/s\nu = 13,750 ft/s\nm₀ = 10,000 lb\n10,000 / m₁ = exp(8000 / 13,750)\n= 1.7893\nm₁ = 5589 kg\nm_fuel = m₀ - m₁ = 10,000 - 5589\nm_fuel = 4410 lb","method":"otro","steps":["Identify the given data: change in velocity (v₁ - v₀), exhaust velocity (u), initial mass (m₀).","Use the given rocket equation: m₀ / m₁ = exp((v₁ - v₀) / u).","Substitute the given values: 10,000 / m₁ = exp(8000 / 13,750).","Calculate the exponential term: exp(8000 / 13,750) ≈ exp(0.5818) ≈ 1.7893.","Solve for m₁: m₁ = 10,000 / 1.7893 ≈ 5589 kg.","Calculate the fuel mass (m_fuel) by subtracting the final mass (m₁) from the initial mass (m₀): m_fuel = m₀ - m₁ = 10,000 lb - 5589 lb.","Perform the subtraction to find the fuel mass: m_fuel = 4410 lb."],"final_answer":"m_fuel = 4410 lb","page_num":928},"14.96":{"problem_text":"Determine the increase in velocity of the communication satellite of Problem 14.95 after 2500 lb of fuel has been consumed.","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["Identify given data from Problem 14.95: initial mass m₀ = 10,000 lb, exhaust velocity u = 13,750 ft/s.","Calculate the final mass m₁ after 2500 lb of fuel is consumed: m₁ = m₀ - m_fuel = 10,000 - 2500 = 7500 lb.","Apply the principle of impulse and momentum to the satellite plus the fuel expelled in time Δt. The initial momentum is mv. The final momentum is (m - Δm)(v + Δv) for the satellite and (Δm)(v + Δv - u) for the expelled fuel. Assuming no external forces, the total momentum is conserved.","Set up the momentum conservation equation: mv = (m - Δm)(v + Δv) + (Δm)(v + Δv - u).","Expand and simplify the equation: mv = mv + m(Δv) - (Δm)v - (Δm)(Δv) + (Δm)v + (Δm)(Δv) - (Δm)u. This simplifies to m(Δv) - (Δm)u = 0.","Rewrite this equation in differential form: m dv = u dm, or dv = (u/m) dm.","Integrate both sides to find the change in velocity. Integrate dv from v₀ to v₁ and integrate dm from m₀ to m₁. However, note the sign convention where dm is the mass expelled, so the mass of the satellite decreases. The correct differential form should be dv = -u (dm/m), where dm is the change in mass of the rocket.","Integrate d(v) from v₀ to v₁ and d(m) from m₀ to m₁, which gives ∫(v₁ to v₀) dv = -u ∫(m₀ to m₁) (dm/m).","Perform the integration: v₁ - v₀ = -u [ln m] from m₀ to m₁, which simplifies to v₁ - v₀ = -u (ln m₁ - ln m₀) = u (ln m₀ - ln m₁) = u ln(m₀/m₁).","Substitute the numerical values: Δv = v₁ - v₀ = 13,750 lb * ln(10,000 lb / 7500 lb).","Calculate the final value: Δv = 13,750 * ln(4/3) ≈ 13,750 * 0.28768 ≈ 3960.6 ft/s."],"final_answer":"Δv = 3960 ft/s","page_num":929},"14.97":{"problem_text":"A 540-kg spacecraft is mounted on top of a rocket with a mass of 19 Mg, including 17.8 Mg of fuel. Knowing that the fuel is consumed at a rate of 225 kg/s and ejected with a relative velocity of 3600 m/s, determine the maximum speed imparted to the spacecraft if the rocket is fired vertically from the ground.","method":"otro","steps":["Identify the given data: u = 3600 m/s, q = 225 kg/s, m_fuel = 17,800 kg. The initial mass of the rocket and spacecraft is m_0 = 19,000 kg (rocket mass) + 540 kg (spacecraft mass) = 19,540 kg.","The velocity equation for a rocket is given by v = u ln(m_0 / (m_0 - qt)) - gt. This equation is referenced from Sample Problem 14.8.","Calculate the time 't' when all fuel has been consumed. Since m_fuel = qt, we have t = m_fuel / q = 17,800 kg / 225 kg/s = 79.111 s.","Maximum velocity is reached when all fuel has been consumed. Substitute qt = m_fuel into the velocity equation to get v_m = u ln(m_0 / (m_0 - m_fuel)) - gt.","Substitute the known values into the maximum velocity equation: v_m = (3600 m/s) ln(19,540 / (19,540 - 17,800)) - (9.81 m/s²)(79.111 s).","Calculate the natural logarithm term: ln(19,540 / 1740) = ln(11.230).","Perform the multiplication for the gravitational term: (9.81 m/s²)(79.111 s) = 776.1 m/s.","Calculate the final maximum velocity: v_m = (3600 m/s) * 11.230 - 776.1 m/s = 40428 m/s - 776.1 m/s = 7930.8 m/s. (Correction: The solution in the image shows 3600 * ln(11.230) = 3600 * 2.4185 ≈ 8706.6, not 40428. There seems to be a calculation error in the provided image for the intermediate step 3600 * 11.230. However, following the image's final calculation for 3600 * ln(11.230) - 776.1 = 7930.8, we'll adhere to that path.)","The image states (3600 m/s) ln 11.230 – 776.1 m/s, and then equals 7930.8 m/s. Let's re-calculate using the natural log: 3600 * ln(11.230) = 3600 * 2.41858 = 8706.888 m/s. Then, 8706.888 m/s - 776.1 m/s = 7930.788 m/s.","Round the result to one decimal place, as typically done in mechanics problems."],"final_answer":"v_m = 7930 m/s","page_num":930},"14.98":{"problem_text":"The rocket used to launch the 540-kg spacecraft of Problem 14.97 is redesigned to include two stages A and B, each of mass 9.5 Mg, including 8.9 Mg of fuel. The fuel is again consumed at a rate of 225 kg/s and ejected with a relative velocity of 3600 m/s. Knowing that when stage A expels its last particle of fuel its casing is released and jettisoned, determine (a) the speed of the rocket at that instant, (b) the maximum speed imparted to the spacecraft.","method":"f-ma","steps":["Define the thrust force as P = u * (dm/dt) = uq, where u is the relative velocity of the ejected fuel and q is the mass flow rate of the fuel.","Express the mass of the rocket and unspent fuel as m = m₀ - qt.","Calculate the corresponding weight force as W = mg.","Determine the acceleration of the rocket using Newton's second law: a = (F - W) / m = (P - W) / m = (uq - mg) / (m₀ - qt) = uq / (m₀ - qt) - g.","Integrate the acceleration with respect to time to obtain the velocity: v = v₀ + ∫adt = v₀ + u∫[q / (m₀ - qt)]dt - ∫gdt. This yields v = v₀ - u ln[(m₀ - qt) / m₀] - gt.","For each stage, identify the given parameters: m_fuel = 8900 kg, u = 3600 m/s, q = 225 kg/s.","Calculate the time duration for burning the fuel: t = m_fuel / q = 8900 kg / 225 kg/s = 39.556 s.","For the first stage (a): The initial velocity v₀ = 0. The initial mass m₀ = 540 kg (spacecraft) + 2 * 9500 kg (two stages) = 19,540 kg.","Calculate the speed at the instant stage A expels its last particle of fuel. At this point, the first stage's fuel is consumed (-8900 kg). So, v₁ = 0 - 3600 ln[(19,540 - 8900) / 19,540] - (9.81)(39.556).","For the second stage (b): The initial velocity for the second stage is v₁ = 1800.1 m/s. The initial mass for the second stage is m₀ = 540 kg (spacecraft) + 9500 kg (remaining stage) = 10,040 kg.","Calculate the maximum speed imparted to the spacecraft after the second stage's fuel is consumed (-8900 kg). So, v₂ = 1800.1 - 3600 ln[(10,040 - 8900) / 10,040] - (9.81)(39.556)."],"final_answer":"(a) v_1 = 1800 m/s; (b) v_2 = 9240 m/s","page_num":931},"14.99":{"problem_text":"Determine the altitude reached by the spacecraft of Problem 14.97 when all the fuel of its launching rocket has been consumed.","method":"otro","steps":["From Sample Problem 14.8, the velocity (v) derivation is given as: v = u ln(m₀ / (m₀ - qt)) - gt = -u ln((m₀ - qt) / m₀) - gt.","Given that g is assumed to be constant, set dy/dt = v and integrate with respect to time to find the altitude h.","The altitude h is given by the integral of velocity with respect to time from 0 to t: h = ∫₀ᵗ v dt = ∫₀ᵗ (u ln(m₀ / (m₀ - qt)) - gt) dt.","This integral can be split into two parts: h = u ∫₀ᵗ ln(m₀ / (m₀ - qt)) dt - ∫₀ᵗ gt dt.","The second part is straightforward: - ∫₀ᵗ gt dt = - (1/2)gt².","For the first part, let z = (m₀ - qt) / m₀. Then dz = -q/m₀ dt, or dt = -m₀/q dz.","When t=0, z=1. When t=t (final time), z_t = (m₀ - qt) / m₀.","So, u ∫₀ᵗ ln(m₀ / (m₀ - qt)) dt = u ∫₁^(z_t) ln(1/z) (-m₀/q) dz = (m₀u/q) ∫_(z_t)^1 ln z dz.","Using integration by parts for ∫ ln z dz = z ln z - z, we get (m₀u/q) [z ln z - z] from z_t to 1.","Evaluate the definite integral: (m₀u/q) [(1 ln 1 - 1) - (z_t ln z_t - z_t)] = (m₀u/q) [-1 - z_t ln z_t + z_t].","Substitute z_t = (m₀ - qt) / m₀ back into the expression.","The expression for h becomes: h = (m₀u/q) [-1 - ((m₀ - qt) / m₀) ln((m₀ - qt) / m₀) + ((m₀ - qt) / m₀)] - (1/2)gt².","Rearranging terms to match the given solution: h = ut + (m₀u/q - ut) ln((m₀ - qt) / m₀) - (1/2)gt².","Further simplification yields: h = u(t - (m₀/q) ln(m₀/(m₀-qt))) - (1/2)gt² which is the compact form shown in the provided solution steps, but the intermediate steps given in the image lead to the final form shown as Eq. (2)."],"final_answer":"h = u(t - (m₀/q) ln(m₀/(m₀-qt))) - (1/2)gt² (Equation 2 in the solution)","page_num":932},"14.100":{"problem_text":"PROBLEM 14.100 (Continued)","method":"otro","steps":["For each stage, given m_fuel = 8900 kg, u = 3600 m/s, q = 225 kg/s. Calculate t = m_fuel / q = 8900 / 225 = 39.556 s.","For the first stage, given v_0 = 0, s_0 = 0. Calculate m_0 = 540 + (2)(9500) = 19,540 kg.","From Eq. (1), calculate v_1 = 0 - 3600 ln((19,540 - 8900) / 19,540) - (9.81)(39.556) = 1800.1 m/s.","From Eq. (2), calculate s_1 = 0 + 0 + 3600 * [39.556 + ( (19,540 / 225) - 39.556 ) * ln((19,540 - 8900) / 19,540)] - (1/2)(9.81)(39.556)^2 = 31,249 m.","Convert h_1 to km: h_1 = 31.2 km.","For the second stage, v_0 = 1800.1 m/s, s_0 = 31,249 m. Calculate m_0 = 540 + 9500 = 10,040 kg.","From Eq. (2), calculate s_2 = 31,249 + (1800.1)(39.556) + 3600 * [39.556 + ( (10,040 / 225) - 39.556 ) * ln((10,040 - 8900) / 10,040)] - (1/2)(9.81)(39.556)^2 = 197,502 m.","Convert h_2 to km: h_2 = 197.5 km."],"final_answer":"h_2 = 197.5 km","page_num":935},"14.101":{"problem_text":"Call the last term x' and let\n\nz = mo - qt / mo\ndz = -q/mo dt or dt = -mo/q dz\n\nx' = (m0 u / q) ∫z0^z ln z dz = (m0 u / q) [ (z ln z + z) ]z0^z\n\n= (m0 u / q) [ ( (m0 - qt / m0) ln(m0 - qt / m0) - 1 ) - ( (1) ln(1) - 1 ) ]\n\n= (m0 u / q) [ ( (1 - qt / m0) ln(1 - qt / m0) - 1 ) - ( -1 ) ]\n\n= (m0 u / q) [ (ln(m0 - qt / m0) - ut) - (ln(m0 - qt / m0) - 1) ]\n\n= ut + (m0 u / q) (ln(m0 - qt / m0) - ut)\n\n= ut - (m0 - t / q) ln(m0 / (m0 - qt) )\n\nx = x0 + v0 t + u t - (m0 - t / q) ln(m0 / (m0 - qt))\n\nData:\nx0 = 0 v0 = 0 q = 37.5 lb/s.\nm0 = 10,000 lb, t = 60 sec u = 13,750 ft/s\nx = 0 + 0 + (13,750) [ 60 - (10,000 / 37.5 - 60) ln(10,000 / (10,000 - (37.5)(60))) ]\n\n= 100,681 ft","method":"otro","steps":["Define a new variable z = (m0 - qt) / m0, and find dz and dt in terms of z and dt or dz.","Express the integral for x' in terms of z and integrate it using the given formula for ∫ ln z dz.","Substitute the limits of integration and simplify the expression for x'.","Further simplify the expression for x' by separating terms and combining constants.","Combine the obtained expression for x' with the general formula for x to get the full equation for x.","Substitute the given numerical values for x0, v0, q, m0, t, and u into the derived equation for x.","Calculate the final value of x.","Convert the final value of x from feet to miles."],"final_answer":"x = 100,681 ft = 19.07 mi","page_num":937},"14.102":{"problem_text":"For the rocket of Problem 14.94, determine (a) the altitude at which all the fuel has been consumed, (b) the velocity of the rocket at that time.\nPROBLEM 14.94 A rocket has a mass of 1200 kg, including 1000 kg of fuel, which is consumed at the rate of 12.5 kg/s and ejected with a relative velocity of 4000 m/s. Knowing that the rocket is fired vertically from the ground, determine its acceleration (a) as it is fired, (b) as the last particle of fuel is being consumed.","method":"otro","steps":["See Sample Problem 14.8 for derivation of the velocity equation, which is given as: v = u ln(m₀ / (m₀ - qt)) - gt.","Note that g is assumed to be constant.","Set dy/dt = v in the velocity equation (1) and integrate with respect to time to find the altitude h.","The integration is given by h = ∫₀ᵗ v dt = ∫₀ᵗ [u ln(m₀ / (m₀ - qt)) - gt] dt.","This integral is broken down into two parts: -u ∫₀ᵗ ln((m₀ - qt) / m₀) dt - (1/2)gt².","To solve ∫ ln((m₀ - qt) / m₀) dt, a substitution is made: Let z = (m₀ - qt) / m₀, so dz = (-q/m₀) dt, or dt = -(m₀/q) dz.","The integral becomes -u ∫ ln(z) (-(m₀/q) dz) = (m₀u/q) ∫ ln(z) dz. Using integration by parts, ∫ ln(z) dz = z ln(z) - z.","Applying the limits from t=0 to t (or z corresponding to these times): h = (m₀u/q) [(z ln z + z)] from z₀ to z - (1/2)gt².","Substituting z = (m₀ - qt) / m₀ and z₀ = 1 (when t=0, z = m₀/m₀ = 1): h = (m₀u/q) [((m₀ - qt)/m₀) ln((m₀ - qt)/m₀) - ((m₀ - qt)/m₀) - (1 ln 1 - 1)] - (1/2)gt².","Simplifying the expression for h: h = (m₀u/q) [(1 - (qt/m₀)) ln((m₀ - qt)/m₀) - (1 - (qt/m₀)) + 1] - (1/2)gt².","Further simplification leads to: h = (m₀u/q) [ln((m₀ - qt)/m₀) - (qt/m₀) ln((m₀ - qt)/m₀) - 1 + (qt/m₀) + 1] - (1/2)gt².","Another form of h is: h = ut + (m₀u/q) ln((m₀ - qt)/m₀) - (1/2)gt².","The final simplified expression for altitude is given as: h = ut + (m₀u/q - ut) ln(m₀ / (m₀ - qt)) - (1/2)gt².","This can be written as: h = u t + (m₀/q - t) u ln(m₀ / (m₀ - qt)) - (1/2)gt²."],"final_answer":"h = ut + (m₀/q - t) u ln(m₀ / (m₀ - qt)) - (1/2)gt²  (2)","page_num":938},"14.103":{"problem_text":"In a jet airplane, the kinetic energy imparted to the exhaust gases is wasted as far as propelling the airplane is concerned. The useful power is equal to the product of the force available to propel the airplane and the speed of the airplane. If v is the speed of the airplane and u is the relative speed of the expelled gases, show that the mechanical efficiency of the airplane is η = 2v/(u+v). Explain why η=1 when u = v.","method":"potencia","steps":["Identify the absolute velocity of exhaust as v_e = u - v.","Define the thrust force F as (dm/dt)(u-v).","Calculate the power of thrust (useful power) P_1 = Fv = (dm/dt)(u-v)v.","Calculate the power associated with exhaust P_2(Δt) = (1/2)(Δm)v_e^2 = (1/2)(Δm)(u-v)^2, which simplifies to P_2 = (1/2)(dm/dt)(u-v)^2.","Calculate the total power supplied by the engine P = P_1 + P_2 = (dm/dt)[(u-v)v + (1/2)(u-v)^2].","Simplify the total power P to (1/2)(dm/dt)(u^2 - v^2).","Define mechanical efficiency η as the ratio of useful power to total power: η = P_1 / P.","Substitute the expressions for P_1 and P into the efficiency formula: η = [(dm/dt)(u-v)v] / [(1/2)(dm/dt)(u^2 - v^2)].","Simplify the expression to get η = [2(u-v)v] / (u^2 - v^2).","Factor the denominator (u^2 - v^2) as (u-v)(u+v).","Cancel out the (u-v) term from the numerator and denominator to get η = 2v / (u+v).","Explain that when u = v, the exhaust has zero velocity and carries no power away, leading to η = 1."],"final_answer":"η = 2v / (u+v)","page_num":940},"14.104":{"problem_text":"In a rocket, the kinetic energy imparted to the consumed and ejected fuel is wasted as far as propelling the rocket is concerned. The useful power is equal to the product of the force available to propel the rocket and the speed of the rocket. If v is the speed of the rocket and u is the relative speed of the expelled fuel, show that the mechanical efficiency of the rocket is η = 2uv/(u² + v²). Explain why η = 1 when u = ν.","method":"potencia","steps":["Define F as the thrust force and dm/dt as the mass flow rate.","The absolute velocity of exhaust is given by ve = u - v.","The thrust force F is calculated as F = (dm/dt)u.","The power of thrust force (useful power) P1 is given by P1 = Fv = (dm/dt)uv.","The power associated with the exhaust (wasted power) P2 is the kinetic energy of the exhaust per unit time: P2 = (1/2)(dm/dt)(u-v)².","The total power supplied by the engine P is the sum of the useful power and the wasted power: P = P1 + P2.","Substitute the expressions for P1 and P2 into the equation for P: P = (dm/dt)uv + (1/2)(dm/dt)(u-v)². Simplify this to P = (dm/2dt)(u²+v²).","The mechanical efficiency η is the ratio of useful power to total power: η = P1/P.","Substitute the expressions for P1 and P: η = [(dm/dt)uv] / [(dm/2dt)(u²+v²)].","Simplify the expression to show η = 2uv / (u²+v²).","Explain that when u = v, η = 1 because the exhaust, having zero velocity, carries no power away."],"final_answer":"η = 2uv / (u² + v²). When u = v, η = 1 because the exhaust, having zero velocity, carries no power away.","page_num":941},"14.105":{"problem_text":"A 30-g bullet is fired with a velocity of 480 m/s into block A, which has a mass of 5 kg. The coefficient of kinetic friction between block A and cart BC is 0.50. Knowing that the cart has a mass of 4 kg and can roll freely, determine (a) the final velocity of the cart and block, (b) the final position of the block on the cart.","method":"trabajo-energia","steps":["Conservation of linear momentum just before impact and after the bullet is embedded in the block A: m₀v₀ = (m₀ + m_A)v'.","Calculate the velocity v' of the block A with the embedded bullet just after impact: (0.030 kg)(480 m/s) = (5.030 kg)v' => v' = (0.030 / 5.030)(480 m/s) = 2.863 m/s.","Conservation of linear momentum from just after impact until the block and cart move together: (m₀ + m_A)v' = (m₀ + m_A + m_C)v_f.","Calculate the final velocity v_f of the cart and block moving together: (5.030 kg)(2.863 m/s) = (9.030 kg)v_f => v_f = (5.030 / 9.030)(2.863 m/s) = 1.5947 m/s ≈ 1.595 m/s.","Calculate the initial kinetic energy of the bullet-block system (just after impact): T' = (1/2)(m₀ + m_A)v'^2 = (1/2)(5.030 kg)(2.863 m/s)^2 = 20.615 J.","Calculate the final kinetic energy of the bullet-block-cart system (when they move together): T_f = (1/2)(m₀ + m_A + m_C)v_f^2 = (1/2)(9.030 kg)(1.5947 m/s)^2 = 11.482 J.","Calculate the friction force F between block A and cart BC: F = μ_k N = μ_k (m₀ + m_A)g = 0.50(5.030 kg)(9.81 m/s^2) = 24.672 N.","Calculate the work done by friction U by the time the block stops sliding relative to the cart: U = -Fx = -24.672x.","Apply the work-energy principle: T' + U = T_f. Substitute the calculated values: 20.615 - 24.672x = 11.482.","Solve for x, the final position of the block on the cart (distance traveled by block A relative to cart BC): 24.672x = 20.615 - 11.482 = 9.133 => x = 9.133 / 24.672 = 0.370 m."],"final_answer":"(a) v_f = 1.595 m/s, (b) x = 0.370 m","page_num":942},"14.106":{"problem_text":"Equating (1) and (3) and solving for vf,","method":"otro","steps":["Equating (1) and (3) and solving for vf, we get:","vf = mA(vA)0 / (mA + mB + mC)","Substituting the given numerical values for masses and initial velocity:","vf = (80 × 10^3)(1.80556) / (130 × 10^3)","Calculating the value of vf:","vf = 1.11111 m/s"],"final_answer":"vf = 4.00 km/h","page_num":944},"14.107":{"problem_text":"Coefficient of restitution. Solving Eqs. (1) and (2) simultaneously, v'_C - v'_{AB} = -e^{-1}(v_{AB} + v_C) = -(0.8)(3 + 4.8).","method":"otro","steps":["La ecuación para el coeficiente de restitución se da como: v'_C - v'_{AB} = -e^{-1}(v_{AB} + v_C)","Se proporcionan los siguientes valores: e = 0.8, v_{AB} = 3 (asumiendo de un paso anterior), v_C = 4.8 (asumiendo de un paso anterior).","Sustituyendo estos valores en la ecuación: v'_C - v'_{AB} = -(0.8)(3 + 4.8)","Calculando el lado derecho de la ecuación: v'_C - v'_{AB} = -(0.8)(7.8) = -6.24","Resolviendo las ecuaciones (1) y (2) simultáneamente para encontrar los valores finales de las velocidades. Las ecuaciones no se muestran completamente aquí, pero los resultados de la solución son:","v'_{AB} = -1.68 mi/h","v'_C = 4.56 mi/h","Se indica que v'_A = v'_B = 1.68 mi/h (asumiendo que 'v_A = v_B' en la notación de la solución se refiere a v'_A y v'_B en mi/h, y dado que la flecha apunta a la misma velocidad para v_A y v_B, y la flecha 'v_C' tiene su propio valor).","Por lo tanto, la velocidad final para A y B es 1.68 mi/h en la dirección opuesta, y para C es 4.56 mi/h."],"final_answer":"v_A = v_B = 1.68 mi/h, v_C = 4.56 mi/h","page_num":946},"14.108":{"problem_text":"A 9000-lb helicopter A was traveling due east in level flight at a speed of 75 mi/h and at an altitude of 2500 ft when it was hit by a 12,000-lb helicopter B. As a result of the collision, both helicopters lost their lift, and their entangled wreckage fell to the ground in 12 s at a point located 1500 ft east and 384 ft south of the point of impact. Neglecting air resistance, determine the velocity components of helicopter B just before the collision.","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["Define a coordinate system: x-axis east, y-axis up, and z-axis south. The origin is the point of collision.","State the initial conditions at the time of collision (t=0): x=0, y=0, z=0.","State the conditions at the time of impact with the ground (t=12 s): x=1500 ft, y=-2500 ft, z=384 ft.","Determine the components of the velocity (v') of the entangled wreckage just after the collision using projectile motion equations:","For the x-direction: x = 0 + v'_x t => 1500 ft = v'_x (12 s) => v'_x = 125 ft/s.","For the y-direction: y = 0 + v'_y t - (1/2)gt^2 => -2500 ft = v'_y (12 s) - (1/2)(32.2 ft/s^2)(12 s)^2 => v'_y = -15.1333 ft/s.","For the z-direction: z = 0 + v'_z t => 384 ft = v'_z (12 s) => v'_z = 32 ft/s.","Express the velocity vector v' of the entangled wreckage: v' = (125 ft/s)i - (15.1333 ft/s)j + (32 ft/s)k.","Convert the velocity of helicopter A from mi/h to ft/s: v_A = (75 mi/h)i = (75 * 5280 / 3600) ft/s i = 110 ft/s i.","Apply the principle of conservation of linear momentum: m_A v_A + m_B v_B = (m_A + m_B) v'.","Rearrange the momentum equation to solve for v_B: v_B = ((m_A + m_B) / m_B) v' - (m_A / m_B) v_A.","Substitute the masses: m_A = 9000 lb, m_B = 12000 lb.","Calculate the ratios: (m_A + m_B) / m_B = (9000 + 12000) / 12000 = 21000 / 12000 = 1.75.","Calculate the ratio: m_A / m_B = 9000 / 12000 = 0.75.","Substitute the values into the equation for v_B:","v_B = (1.75)(125i - 15.1333j + 32k) - (0.75)(110i)","v_B = (218.75i - 26.483j + 56k) - (82.5i)","v_B = (218.75 - 82.5)i - 26.483j + 56k","v_B = 136.25 ft/s i - 26.483 ft/s j + 56 ft/s k.","Convert the components of v_B back to mi/h for the final answer (by multiplying by 3600/5280):","v_Bx = 136.25 ft/s = 136.25 * (3600/5280) mi/h = 92.897 mi/h (approximately 92.9 mi/h east).","v_By = -26.483 ft/s = -26.483 * (3600/5280) mi/h = -18.056 mi/h (approximately 18.06 mi/h down).","v_Bz = 56 ft/s = 56 * (3600/5280) mi/h = 38.181 mi/h (approximately 38.2 mi/h south)."],"final_answer":"Components of v_B: 92.9 mi/h east, 38.2 mi/h south, 18.06 mi/h down","page_num":947},"14.3":{"problem_text":"A 180-lb man and a 120-lb woman stand side by side at the same end of a 300-lb boat, ready to dive, each with a 16-ft/s velocity relative to the boat. Determine the velocity of the boat after they have both dived, if (a) the woman dives first, (b) the man dives first.","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["Identify given parameters: man's weight = 180 lb, woman's weight = 120 lb, boat's weight = 300 lb, relative diving velocity = 16 ft/s for both.","Part (a): Woman dives first. Apply conservation of momentum for the woman and the boat (initially at rest). The initial momentum is 0. The final momentum is the sum of the momentum of the boat with the man, and the momentum of the woman. The woman's velocity relative to the boat is 16 ft/s. Her absolute velocity is (16 - v1), where v1 is the boat's velocity after the woman dives. Solve for v1.","After the woman dives, the man on the boat then dives. Apply conservation of momentum for the man and the boat. The initial momentum is the momentum of the boat with the man (mass = 300+180 lb) moving at v1. The final momentum is the sum of the momentum of the boat (mass = 300 lb) moving at v2, and the momentum of the man (mass = 180 lb). The man's velocity relative to the boat is 16 ft/s. His absolute velocity is (16 - v2). Solve for v2.","Part (b): Man dives first. Apply conservation of momentum for the man and the boat (initially at rest). The initial momentum is 0. The final momentum is the sum of the momentum of the boat with the woman, and the momentum of the man. The man's velocity relative to the boat is 16 ft/s. His absolute velocity is (16 - v'1), where v'1 is the boat's velocity after the man dives. Solve for v'1.","After the man dives, the woman on the boat then dives. Apply conservation of momentum for the woman and the boat. The initial momentum is the momentum of the boat with the woman (mass = 300+120 lb) moving at v'1. The final momentum is the sum of the momentum of the boat (mass = 300 lb) moving at v'2, and the momentum of the woman (mass = 120 lb). The woman's velocity relative to the boat is 16 ft/s. Her absolute velocity is (16 - v'2). Solve for v'2."],"final_answer":"a) v2 = 9.20 ft/s; b) v'2 = 9.37 ft/s","page_num":799},"14.8":{"problem_text":"At an amusement park, there are 200-kg bumper cars A, B, and C that have riders with masses of 40 kg, 60 kg, and 35 kg, respectively. Car A is moving to the right with a velocity vA = 2 m/s when it hits stationary car B. The coefficient of restitution between each car is 0.8. Determine the velocity of car C so that after car B collides with car C, the velocity of car B is zero.","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["Assume that each car with its rider may be treated as a particle. Calculate the total masses of each car with its rider: mA = 200 + 40 = 240 kg, mB = 200 + 60 = 260 kg, mC = 200 + 35 = 235 kg.","Identify initial velocities: vA = 2 m/s, vB = 0, vC = ? (to be determined later). Assume velocities are positive to the right.","For the first impact between car A and car B: Apply the principle of conservation of momentum. mAvA + mBvB = mAvA' + mBvB'. Substitute initial values: (240)(2) + (260)(0) = 240vA' + 260vB'. This gives Equation (1): 480 = 240vA' + 260vB'.","Apply the coefficient of restitution for cars A and B: vB' - vA' = e(vA - vB). Substitute values: vB' - vA' = (0.8)(2 - 0) = 1.6. This gives Equation (2): vB' - vA' = 1.6.","Solve Equations (1) and (2) simultaneously to find the velocities after the first impact. From (2), vB' = vA' + 1.6. Substitute into (1): 480 = 240vA' + 260(vA' + 1.6). 480 = 240vA' + 260vA' + 416. 64 = 500vA'. vA' = 0.128 m/s. Then vB' = 0.128 + 1.6 = 1.728 m/s.","For the second impact between car B and car C: The problem states that after car B collides with car C, the velocity of car B is zero (vB'' = 0). Let vC'' be the velocity of car C after this impact.","Apply the coefficient of restitution for cars B and C: vC'' - vB'' = e(vB' - vC). Substitute given values and vB'' = 0: vC'' - 0 = (0.8)(1.728 - vC). This simplifies to vC'' = 1.3824 - 0.8vC."],"final_answer":"vC'' = 1.3824 - 0.8vC","page_num":806},"14.12":{"problem_text":"For the system of particles of Problem 14.11, determine (a) the components vₓ and vᵧ of the velocity of particle B for which the angular momentum Hₒ of the system about O is parallel to the y-axis, (b) the corresponding value of Hₒ.\nPROBLEM 14.11 A system consists of three particles A, B, and C. We know that mₐ = 3 kg, mʙ = 4 kg, and m𝒸 = 5 kg and that the velocities of the particles expressed in m/s are, respectively, vₐ = −4i + 4j + 6k, vʙ = vₓi + vᵧj + 4k, and v𝒸 = 2i − 6j − 4k. Determine (a) the components vₓ and vᵧ of the velocity of particle B for which the angular momentum Hₒ of the system about O is parallel to the z axis, (b) the corresponding value of Hₒ.","method":"otro","steps":["Calculate the angular momentum Hₒ of the system using the superposition principle: Hₒ = rₐ × mₐvₐ + rʙ × mʙvʙ + r𝒸 × m𝒸v𝒸.","The position vectors are: rₐ = (1.2 m)i + (1.5 m)k, rʙ = (0.9 m)i + (1.2 m)j + (1.2 m)k, r𝒸 = (0.5 m)i + (2.4 m)j + (1.8 m)k.","The masses and velocities are: mₐ = 3 kg, vₐ = −4i + 4j + 6k; mʙ = 4 kg, vʙ = vₓi + vᵧj + 4k; m𝒸 = 5 kg, v𝒸 = 2i − 6j − 4k.","Formulate the cross products mₐ(rₐ × vₐ), mʙ(rʙ × vʙ), and m𝒸(r𝒸 × v𝒸) using determinants.","Sum the components of the cross products to find the components of Hₒ: Hₒ = (7.2 − 4.8vᵧ)i + (−36 + 4.8vₓ)j + (−9.6 + 3.6vᵧ − 4.8vₓ)k.","For Hₒ to be parallel to the y-axis, the x and z components must be zero: Hₓ = 7.2 − 4.8vᵧ = 0 and H₂ = −9.6 + 3.6vᵧ − 4.8vₓ = 0.","Solve the equation Hₓ = 0 for vᵧ: vᵧ = 7.2 / 4.8 = 1.500 m/s.","Substitute vᵧ into the equation H₂ = 0: −9.6 + 3.6(1.500) − 4.8vₓ = 0.","Solve for vₓ: −9.6 + 5.4 − 4.8vₓ = 0, which gives −4.2 − 4.8vₓ = 0, so vₓ = −4.2 / 4.8 = −0.875 m/s.","The components of the velocity of particle B are vₓ = −0.875 m/s and vᵧ = 1.500 m/s.","For part (b), calculate the corresponding value of Hₒ. Since Hₒ is parallel to the y-axis, Hₒ = Hᵧj.","Substitute the values of vₓ and vᵧ into the expression for Hᵧ: Hᵧ = −36 + 4.8vₓ = −36 + 4.8(−0.875).","Hᵧ = −36 − 4.2 = −40.2 kg·m²/s."],"final_answer":"(a) vₓ = -0.875 m/s, vᵧ = 1.500 m/s; (b) Hₒ = -(40.2 kg·m²/s)j","page_num":812},"14.13":{"problem_text":"A system consists of three particles A, B, and C. We know that WA = 5lb, WB = 4lb, and WC = 3 lb, and that the velocities of the particles expressed in ft/s are, respectively, vA = 2i+3j-2k, vB = vxi+vyj+vzk, and vC = -3i-2j+k. Determine (a) the components vx and vz of the velocity of particle B for which the angular momentum HO of the system about O is parallel to the x axis, (b) the value of HO.","method":"otro","steps":["Identify the position vectors for each particle. For particle A: rA = (5 ft)i + (4 ft)j + (0 ft)k. For particle B: rB = (2 ft)i + (4 ft)j + (3 ft)k. For particle C: rC = (3 ft)i + (6 ft)j + (8 ft)k.","Formulate the angular momentum H_O of the system about O using the formula H_O = Σ(r_i x m_i v_i). This involves calculating the cross product of the position vector and the momentum for each particle and then summing them.","Express the angular momentum H_O in its component form (H_x)i + (H_y)j + (H_z)k after performing the cross products and summations. This results in H_O = (1/g)[(16v_x - 116)i + (12v_z - 16v_x + 16)j + ((-16v_z - 12)k].","For H_O to be parallel to the x-axis, the y and z components of H_O must be zero. Set H_y = 0 and H_z = 0.","Solve the equation for H_z = 0: -16v_z - 12 = 0 to find v_z.","Substitute the value of v_z into the equation for H_y = 0: 12v_z - 16v_x + 16 = 0, and solve for v_x.","Substitute the determined values of v_x and v_z back into the x-component of H_O: H_O = (1/g)(16v_x - 116)i to find the magnitude of H_O."],"final_answer":"(a) v_x = -0.75 ft/s, v_z = 0.4375 ft/s; (b) H_O = -(3.39 ft·lb·s)i","page_num":813},"14.24":{"problem_text":"In a scattering experiment, an alpha particle A is projected with the velocity u0 = -(600 m/s)i+ (750 m/s)j- (800 m/s)k into a stream of oxygen nuclei moving with the common velocity v0 = (600 m/s)j. After colliding successively with nuclei B and C, particle A is observed to move along the path defined by the Points A1 (280, 240, 120) and A2(360, 320, 160), while nuclei B and C are observed to move along paths defined, respectively, by B1(147, 220, 130), B2(114, 290, 120), and by C1(240, 232, 90) and C2(240, 280, 75). All paths are along straight lines and all coordinates are expressed in millimeters. Knowing that the mass of an oxygen nucleus is four times that of an alpha particle, determine the speed of each of the three particles after the collisions.","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["Calculate the position vectors for A, B, and C as the difference between the final and initial points of each path (A1A2, B1B2, C1C2).","Determine the magnitude of each position vector.","Derive the unit vectors (λA, λB, λC) for each path by dividing the position vector by its magnitude.","Express the velocity vectors after collision (vA, vB, vC) in terms of their speed and the calculated unit vectors.","Apply the principle of conservation of momentum: mu0 + 4mv0 + 4mv0 = mvA + 4mvB + 4mvC, where m is the mass of the alpha particle and 4m is the mass of the oxygen nucleus.","Divide the momentum equation by m to simplify, and substitute the given initial velocities and the expressions for the final velocities.","Resolve the resulting vector equation into its i, j, and k components, forming a system of linear equations.","Solve the system of equations for vA, vB, and vC (this step is not shown in the provided snippet but is implied by the setup)."],"final_answer":null,"page_num":826},"14.29":{"problem_text":"Consider the frame of reference Ax'y'z' in translation with respect to the newtonian frame of reference Oxyz. We define the angular momentum H'A of a system of n particles about A as the sum\n(1)\nof the moments about A of the momenta mᵢv'ᵢ of the particles in their motion relative to the frame Ax'y'z'. Denoting by H_A the sum\n(2)\nof the moments about A of the momenta mᵢvᵢ of the particles in their motion relative to the newtonian frame Oxyz, show that H_A = H'A at a given instant if, and only if, one of the following conditions is satisfied at that instant: (a) A has zero velocity with respect to the frame Oxyz, (b) A coincides with the mass center G of the system, (c) the velocity v_A relative to Oxyz is directed along the line AG.","method":"otro","steps":["Start with the definition of the velocity of a particle in the Newtonian frame and the moving frame: vᵢ = v_A + v'ᵢ.","Substitute this into the expression for H_A: H_A = Σ(r'ᵢ × mᵢvᵢ) = Σ(r'ᵢ × mᵢ(v_A + v'ᵢ)).","Expand the sum: H_A = Σ(r'ᵢ × mᵢv_A) + Σ(r'ᵢ × mᵢv'ᵢ).","Recognize that the second term is H'A: H_A = Σ(r'ᵢ × mᵢv_A) + H'A.","Factor out v_A from the first term: H_A = (Σmᵢr'ᵢ) × v_A + H'A.","Substitute r'ᵢ = rᵢ - r_A: H_A = (Σmᵢ(rᵢ - r_A)) × v_A + H'A.","If H_A = H'A, then (Σmᵢ(rᵢ - r_A)) × v_A = 0.","This condition, m(r̄ - r_A) × v_A = 0, is satisfied if any of the following are true:","(a) v_A = 0 (Point A has zero velocity).","(b) r̄ = r_A (Point A coincides with the mass center, as r̄ is the position vector of the mass center).","(c) v_A is parallel to r̄ - r_A (The velocity v_A is directed along the line AG)."],"final_answer":"H_A = H'A if and only if m(r̄ - r_A) × v_A = 0, which is satisfied if (a) v_A = 0, (b) r̄ = r_A, or (c) v_A is parallel to r̄ - r_A.","page_num":834},"14.42":{"problem_text":"Solve Problem 14.41, knowing that the cord is severed when \\theta = 120°.\nPROBLEM 14.41 Two hemispheres are held together by a cord which maintains a spring under compression (the spring is not attached to the hemispheres). The potential energy of the compressed spring is 120 J and the assembly has an initial velocity \\nu_0 of magnitude \\nu_0 = 8 m/s. Knowing that the cord is severed when \\theta=30°, causing the hemispheres to fly apart, determine the resulting velocity of each hemisphere.","method":"otro","steps":["Use a frame of reference moving with the mass center.","Conservation of momentum: \\qquad 0=-m_A \\nu_A' + m_B \\nu_B'","Thus, \\nu_A' = \\frac{m_B}{m_A} \\nu_B'","Conservation of energy: \\qquad V = \\frac{1}{2} m_A (\\nu_A')^2 + \\frac{1}{2} m_B (\\nu_B')^2","Substitute \\nu_A' into the energy equation: \\qquad V = \\frac{1}{2} m_A \\left(\\frac{m_B}{m_A} \\nu_B'\\right)^2 + \\frac{1}{2} m_B (\\nu_B')^2","Simplify to get: \\qquad V = \\frac{m_B(m_A+m_B)}{2m_A} (\\nu_B')^2","Solve for \\nu_B': \\qquad \\nu_B' = \\sqrt{\\frac{2m_A V}{m_B(m_A+m_B)}}","Given data: m_A=2.5 kg, m_B=1.5 kg, V=120 J.","Calculate \\nu_B' using the given data: \\qquad \\nu_B' = \\sqrt{\\frac{(2)(2.5)(120)}{(1.5)(2.5+1.5)}} = \\sqrt{\\frac{600}{1.5 \\times 4}} = \\sqrt{\\frac{600}{6}} = \\sqrt{100} = 10 m/s","The angle for \\nu_B' is 60° (since the given angle for severing is 120°, and velocities are relative to the mass center along the line of action, the actual separation angle from the original direction of motion is \\theta/2). So, \\nu_B' = 10 m/s \\angle 60°","Calculate \\nu_A' using the relation \\nu_A' = \\frac{m_B}{m_A} \\nu_B': \\qquad \\nu_A' = \\frac{1.5}{2.5}(10) = 6 m/s","The angle for \\nu_A' is -60° (opposite to \\nu_B'). So, \\nu_A' = 6 m/s \\angle -60° . Note: The solution uses an angle of 60°. There might be a convention for direction relative to the initial velocity, but for separation, they should be in opposite directions.","Now, consider the original velocity \\nu_0 = 8 m/s. We add \\nu_0 to the relative velocities \\nu_A' and \\nu_B' to find the final absolute velocities \\nu_A and \\nu_B.","For \\nu_A: \\nu_A = [8 m/s \\rightarrow] + [6 m/s \\angle -60°] (Here the solution provided shows 60 deg, but vector addition would need to account for components. If 60° is used for \\nu_A, it implies separation is symmetric around the initial velocity after some coordinate system transformation. For 120° separation angle, the velocities relative to center of mass would be at \\pm 120/2 = \\pm 60° from the relative separation axis, but typically the components are considered horizontally and vertically, with respect to the initial velocity.) The specific vector addition components are not shown, but result in \\nu_A = 12.17 m/s \\angle 25.3°","For \\nu_B: \\nu_B = [8 m/s \\rightarrow] + [10 m/s \\angle 60°] (Again, the specific vector addition components are not shown. Relative velocity for B was 10m/s at 60°. Initial velocity is at 0°.) This results in \\nu_B = 9.17 m/s \\angle 70.9°"],"final_answer":"\\nu_A = 12.17 m/s \\angle 25.3°, \\nu_B = 9.17 m/s \\angle 70.9°","page_num":851},"14.72":{"problem_text":"In order to shorten the distance required for landing, a jet airplane is equipped with movable vanes, which partially reverse the direction of the air discharged by each of its engines. Each engine scoops in the air at a rate of 120 kg/s and discharges it with a velocity of 600 m/s relative to the engine. At an instant when the speed of the airplane is 270 km/h, determine the reverse thrust provided by each of the engines.","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["Apply the impulse-momentum principle to the moving air, using a frame of reference that is moving with the airplane. Let F be the force on the air.","Convert the airplane speed from km/h to m/s: v = 270 km/h = 75 m/s.","Identify the velocity of the discharged air relative to the engine: u = 600 m/s.","Apply the impulse-momentum equation: - (Δm)v + F(Δt) = 2 * (Δm/2) * u sin 20°.","Rearrange the equation to solve for F: F = (Δm/Δt) * (v + u sin 20°).","Substitute the given values: mass flow rate (dm/dt) = 120 kg/s, v = 75 m/s, u = 600 m/s, and the angle 20°.","Calculate F = (120 kg/s) * (75 m/s + 600 m/s * sin 20°).","Compute the numerical value for F, which represents the force on the air.","The reverse thrust provided by each engine (Force on airplane) is -F."],"final_answer":"F = 33.6 kN","page_num":900},"14.78":{"problem_text":"For a certain wind speed, the wind turbine-generator shown produces 28 kW of electric power and has an efficiency of 0.35 as an energy-conversion system. Assuming ρ = 1.21 kg/m³ for air determine (a) the kinetic energy of the air particles entering the 7.50-m-diameter circle per second, (b) the wind speed.","method":"potencia","steps":["Calculate the input power using the output power and efficiency: input power = output power / efficiency = 28 kW / 0.35 = 80 kW = 80 kJ/s. This represents the kinetic energy per second of the air particles.","Formulate the kinetic energy per second as (1/2) * (Δm/Δt) * v², where Δm/Δt is the mass flow rate.","Substitute Δm/Δt = ρ * Q = ρ * A * v, where ρ is the air density, A is the area swept by the blades, and v is the wind speed.","The kinetic energy per second equation becomes (1/2) * ρ * A * v³. The area A is given by π * (D/2)² = π * (7.50 m / 2)² = π/4 * (7.50 m)².","Set the kinetic energy per second (80 kJ/s) equal to the derived expression: 80 kJ/s = (1/2) * (1.21 kg/m³) * (π/4 * (7.50 m)²) * v³.","Solve for v³: v³ = 2993.1.","Calculate v by taking the cube root of v³: v = 14.411 m/s.","Convert the wind speed from m/s to km/h: v = 14.411 m/s * (3600 s / 1 h) * (1 km / 1000 m) = 51.9 km/h."],"final_answer":"(a) Kinetic energy per second = 80 kJ/s, (b) v = 51.9 km/h","page_num":907},"14.4":{"problem_text":"A 180-lb man and a 120-lb woman stand at opposite ends of a 300-lb boat, ready to dive, each with a 16-ft/s velocity relative to the boat. Determine the velocity of the boat after they have both dived, if (a) the woman dives first, (b) the man dives first.","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["Part (a) Woman dives first:","Apply the conservation of momentum when the woman dives: 0 = (120/g)(16 - v1) + (300 + 180)/g * v1. Solve for v1.","Momentum after woman dives: v1 = (120)(16)/600 = 3.20 ft/s.","Apply the conservation of momentum when the man dives next: Momentum before man dives = Momentum after man dives.","Initial momentum of boat + man system: (300+180)/g * v1.","Final momentum of boat + man system: (300/g) * v2 + (180/g) * (16 - v2). Note that relative velocity is (16 - v2) if v2 is in the opposite direction.","Set up the equation: (300+180)/g * v1 = (300/g) * v2 + (180/g) * (16 - v2).","Simplify and solve for v2: 480v1 = 300v2 + 180(16 - v2).","Substitute v1 = 3.20 ft/s: 480(3.20) + (180)(16) = (300 + 180)v2.  This simplifies to 480v1 + 180(16) = 480v2. So, v2 = (480v1 + 180(16))/480.","Calculate v2: v2 = (480 * 3.20 + 180 * 16) / 480 = 2.80 ft/s.","Part (b) Man dives first:","Apply the conservation of momentum when the man dives: 0 = (180/g)(16 - v'1) + (300 + 120)/g * v'1. Solve for v'1.","Momentum after man dives: v'1 = (180)(16)/600 = 4.80 ft/s.","Apply the conservation of momentum when the woman dives next: Momentum before woman dives = Momentum after woman dives.","Initial momentum of boat + woman system: (300+120)/g * v'1.","Final momentum of boat + woman system: (300/g) * v'2 + (120/g) * (16 - v'2). Note that relative velocity is (16 - v'2) if v'2 is in the opposite direction, assuming positive direction is the direction of man's dive.","Set up the equation: (300+120)/g * v'1 = (300/g) * v'2 + (120/g) * (16 - v'2).","Simplify and solve for v'2: 420v'1 = 300v'2 + 120(16 - v'2).","Substitute v'1 = 4.80 ft/s: -420v'1 + (120)(16) = (300 + 120)v'2. So, v'2 = (-420v'1 + 120(16))/420.  The negative sign for first term means the boat's initial velocity after man dives is taken in the opposite direction.","Calculate v'2: v'2 = (-420 * 4.80 + 120 * 16) / 420 = -0.229 ft/s."],"final_answer":" (a) v2 = 2.80 ft/s, (b) v'2 = -0.229 ft/s","page_num":800},"14.109":{"problem_text":"PROBLEM 14.109 (Continued)","method":"trabajo-energia","steps":["T₁ + V₁ = T₂ + V₂","0 + 27 = 0.10352v²_A + 2.5","v²_A = 236.67 ft²"],"final_answer":"v_A = 15.38 ft/s, v_B = 5.13 ft/s","page_num":949},"14.110":{"problem_text":"A 9-kg block B starts from rest and slides down the inclined surface of a 15-kg wedge A, which is supported by a horizontal surface. Neglecting friction, determine (a) the velocity of B relative to A after it has slid 0.6 m down the surface of the wedge, (b) the corresponding velocity of the wedge.","method":"trabajo-energia","steps":["We resolve v_B into its components: v_A and v_B/A 30°","Impulse-momentum principle.","x component: C + 0 = m_B v_B/A cos 30° - m_A v_A - m_B v_A","v_A = (m_B cos 30° / (m_A + m_B)) v_B/A = (9 kg cos 30° / (15 kg + 9 kg)) v_B/A","v_A = 0.32476 v_B/A (1)","Conservation of energy.","T_0 = 0","V_0 = m_B g h = (9 kg)(9.81 m/s²)(0.6 m)sin 30° = 26.487 J","T = 1/2 m_A v_A^2 + 1/2 m_B v_B^2","V = 0","Referring to figures shown above and using the law of cosines: T = 1/2 m_A v_A^2 + 1/2 m_B (v_A^2 + v_B/A^2 - 2v_A v_B/A cos 30°)","Recalling Eq. (1) and substituting the given data:","T = 1/2 (15)(0.32476)^2 v_B/A^2 + 1/2 (9)[(0.32476)^2 v_B/A^2 + v_B/A^2 - 2(0.32476) v_B/A^2 cos 30°]","T = 0.79102 v_B/A^2 + 2.04336 v_B/A^2 = 3.2344 v_B/A^2","T + V = T_0 + V_0: 3.2344 v_B/A^2 = 26.487 J","v_B/A = 2.8617 m/s"],"final_answer":"v_B/A = 2.8617 m/s","page_num":950},"14.111":{"problem_text":"...","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["Principle of impulse and momentum:","Diagrammatic representation of momentum conservation: initial momentum (Δm)v, impulse B(Δt), and final momentum (Δm)v'","Equation derived from the principle: (Δm)v + B(Δt) = (Δm)v'","Solving for B: B = (Δm/Δt)(v' - v) = q√2gh(-cos 30°i - sin 30°j + j)","Calculating the x-component of B: Bx = -√2gh cos 30° = - (√3/2)√2gh","Calculating the y-component of B: By = √2gh(1 - sin 30°) = (1/2)√2gh","The final magnitude and direction of B are given as B = √2gh ⦟ 30°"],"final_answer":"B = √2gh ⦟ 30°","page_num":953},"14.112":{"problem_text":"The final component of a conveyor system receives sand at a rate of 100 kg/s at A and discharges it at B. The sand is moving horizontally at A and B with a velocity of magnitude vA = vB = 4.5 m/s. Knowing that the combined weight of the component and of the sand it supports is W = 4 kN, determine the reactions at C and D.","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["Apply the impulse-momentum principle.","Calculate moments about C:","-(0.9)(Δm)vA + 3D(Δt) - 1.8W(Δt) = -(1.65)(Δm)vB","Substitute Δm = ṁΔt and rearrange to solve for D:","D = (1.8/3)W + (1/3)(Δm/Δt)(0.9vA - 1.65vB)","D = (1.8/3)(4000) + (1/3)(100)[(0.9)(4.5) - (1.65)(4.5)]","Calculate the x components:","(Δm)vA + Cx(Δt) = (Δm)vB","Cx = (Δm/Δt)(vB - vA) = (100)(4.5 - 4.5) = 0","Calculate the y components:","0 + Cy(Δt) + D(Δt) - W(Δt) = 0","Cy = W - D","Substitute the calculated value of D into the equation for Cy.","Cy = 4000 - 2287.5"],"final_answer":"D = 2.29 kN↑, C = 1.712 kN↑","page_num":954},"14.113":{"problem_text":"A garden sprinkler has four rotating arms, each of which consists of two horizontal straight sections of pipe forming an angle of 120° with each other. Each arm discharges water at a rate of 20 L/min with a velocity of 18 m/s relative to the arm. Knowing that the friction between the moving and stationary parts of the sprinkler is equivalent to a couple of magnitude M=0.375 N⋅m, determine the constant rate at which the sprinkler rotates.","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["Calculate the mass flow rate per arm: Q = (20 L/min) / (1000 L/m³) * (1 min / 60 s) = 333.33 x 10^-6 m³/s. Then, dm/dt = ρQ = (1000 kg/m³)(333.33 x 10^-6 m³/s) = 0.33333 kg/s.","Consider the geometry of triangle OAB. Using the law of cosines, (OA)² = 150² + 100² - (2)(150)(100)cos120°. Calculate OA = 217.95 mm = 0.21795 m.","Using the law of sines, sinβ / 100 = sin120° / 217.95. Solve for β = 23.413°. Then, α = 60° - β = 36.587°.","Apply the impulse-momentum principle for moments about O. (Δm)(v₀)(0) + M₀(Δt) = (OA)(Δm)v_r sinα - (OA)(Δm)(OA)ω. This simplifies to M₀ = (dm/dt)[(OA)v_r sinα - (OA)²ω].","Substitute the numerical values: M₀ = (0.33333 kg/s)[(0.21795 m)(18 m/s)sin36.587° - (0.21795 m)²ω].","Calculate the expression: M₀ = 0.77945 - 0.015834ω.","The moment that the stream exerts on the arm is -M₀.","Balance the friction couple and the four streams: M_friction - 4M₀ = 0. Substitute M_friction = 0.375 N⋅m. So, 0.375 - 4(0.77945 - 0.015834ω) = 0.","Solve for ω: 0.375 - 3.1178 + 0.063336ω = 0. So, 0.063336ω = 2.7428. Thus, ω = 43.305 rad/s.","Convert to rpm: ω = 43.305 rad/s * (1 rev / 2π rad) * (60 s / 1 min) = 413.56 rpm. Round to 414 rpm."],"final_answer":"ω = 414 rpm","page_num":955},"14.114":{"problem_text":"The ends of a chain lie in piles at A and C. When given an initial speed v, the chain keeps moving freely at that speed over the pulley at B. Neglecting friction, determine the required value of h.","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["Let ρ be the mass per unit length of chain. Consider the impulse-momentum applied to the link being brought to rest at Point C.","Calculate Δm: Δm = ρ(Δl) = ρv(Δt).","Apply the impulse-momentum principle to the link at C: -(Δm)v + CΔt = 0.","Substitute Δm: -ρv(Δt)v + CΔt = 0.","Solve for C: C = ρv².","Consider the impulse-momentum applied to the moving portion of the chain. Only the changes in momentum and forces contributing to moments about O in the diagram are considered.","Apply the sum of moments about O: (Δm)v + [ρgh - C]Δt = (Δm)v.","Simplify the moment equation to find C: C = ρgh.","Equate the two expressions for C: ρv² = ρgh.","Solve for h: h = v²/g."],"final_answer":"h = v²/g","page_num":956},"14.115":{"problem_text":"A railroad car of length L and mass m₀ when empty is moving freely on a horizontal track while being loaded with sand from a stationary chute at a rate dm/dt = q. Knowing that the car was approaching the chute at a speed v₀, determine (a) the mass of the car and its load after the car has cleared the chute, (b) the speed of the car at that time.","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["Consider the conservation of the horizontal component of momentum of the railroad car of mass m₀ and the sand mass qt.","The initial momentum is m₀v₀.","The mass at time t is m₀ + qt, and the velocity is v. So, the momentum at time t is (m₀ + qt)v.","Equating initial and final momentum: m₀v₀ = (m₀ + qt)v.","Solve for v: v = m₀v₀ / (m₀ + qt). This is Equation (1).","We know that v = dx/dt, so dx/dt = m₀v₀ / (m₀ + qt).","To find the time t_L when the car clears the chute (i.e., x = L), we integrate the expression for dx/dt from x=0 to x=L and t=0 to t=t_L.","L = ∫₀ᵀᴸ v dt = ∫₀ᵀᴸ [m₀v₀ / (m₀ + qt)] dt.","Integrate the right side: L = (m₀v₀ / q) [ln(m₀ + qt_L) - ln(m₀)].","Simplify to: L = (m₀v₀ / q) ln[(m₀ + qt_L) / m₀].","Rearrange the equation to solve for (m₀ + qt_L): ln[(m₀ + qt_L) / m₀] = qL / (m₀v₀).","Exponentiate both sides: (m₀ + qt_L) / m₀ = e^(qL / (m₀v₀)).","Solve for (m₀ + qt_L): m₀ + qt_L = m₀e^(qL / (m₀v₀)). This is the final mass of the railroad car and sand when it has cleared the chute.","Substitute the expression for (m₀ + qt_L) into Equation (1) to find the speed v_L when the car has cleared the chute.","v_L = m₀v₀ / (m₀ + qt_L) = m₀v₀ / [m₀e^(qL / (m₀v₀))].","Simplify to: v_L = v₀e^(-qL / (m₀v₀))."],"final_answer":"(a) m₀ + qt_L = m₀e^(qL / (m₀v₀)) (b) v_L = v₀e^(-qL / (m₀v₀))","page_num":957},"14.116":{"problem_text":"A possible method for reducing the speed of a training plane as it lands on an aircraft carrier consists in having the tail of the plane hook into the end of a heavy chain of length l which lies in a pile below deck. Denoting by m the mass of the plane and by v₀ its speed at touchdown, and assuming no other retarding force, determine (a) the required mass of the chain if the speed of the plane is to be reduced to βv₀, where β<1, (b) the maximum value of the force exerted by the chain on the plane.","method":"impulso-momento","steps":["Let m' be the mass of the chain per unit length and x be the distance traveled in time t. Let v be the velocity of the plane at time t. Apply the principle of conservation of linear momentum.","Formulate the x-component of the linear momentum balance: mv₀ = (m + m'x)v.","Express the velocity v as a function of m, m', v₀, and x: v = mv₀ / (m + m'x). (1)","For part (a), determine the required mass of the chain. The speed is reduced to βv₀ when x = l (the full length of the chain is picked up).","Substitute these conditions into the velocity equation: βv₀ = mv₀ / (m + m'l).","Solve for m'l, which represents the total mass of the chain required: m'l = (1 - β) / β * m.","For part (b), determine the maximum force on the plane. First, find the acceleration of the plane.","Differentiate the velocity v with respect to time t to find acceleration a = dv/dt. Using the chain rule, a = v * dv/dx.","Calculate dv/dx from the velocity equation: dv/dx = -m'mv₀ / (m + m'x)².","Substitute dv/dx and v into the acceleration equation: a = [-m'mv₀ / (m + m'x)²] * [mv₀ / (m + m'x)] = -m'm²v₀² / (m + m'x)³.","Apply Newton's second law, F = (m + m'x)a, to find the force acting on the plane. Note that the mass resisting acceleration is (m + m'x).","F = (m + m'x) * [-m'm²v₀² / (m + m'x)³] = -m'm²v₀² / (m + m'x)².","The maximum force occurs when x = 0 (at touchdown, as the chain begins to be picked up).","Substitute x = 0 into the force equation: |F_max| = m'm²v₀² / m² = m'v₀².","Substitute the expression for m' from part (a) (m' = (1 - β)m / lβ) into the maximum force equation: |F_max| = [(1 - β)m / lβ] * v₀².","The final expression for the maximum force is |F_max| = (1 - β)mv₀² / (βl)."],"final_answer":" (a) The required mass of the chain (m'l) = (1 - β) / β * m. (b) The maximum value of the force exerted by the chain on the plane (|F_max|) = (1 - β)mv₀² / (βl).","page_num":958},"14.1":{"problem_text":"Airline employee tosses 15-kg and 20-kg suitcases onto 25-kg carrier.","method":"Conservacion de momento lineal - impactos sucesivos","steps":["No hay fuerzas externas horizontales. El carrito rueda libremente entre impactos.","(a) 15-kg primero: (15)(3) = (40)v1  →  v1 = 1.125 m/s","(20)(2) + (40)(1.125) = (60)v2  →  v2 = 1.417 m/s","(b) 20-kg primero: (20)(2) = (45)v1  →  v1 = 0.8889 m/s","(15)(3) + (45)(0.8889) = (60)v2  →  v2 = 1.417 m/s"],"final_answer":"(a) v2 = 1.417 m/s  |  (b) v2 = 1.417 m/s","page_num":797},"14.5":{"problem_text":"Bullet 1500 ft/s through 6-lb block A, embeds in 4.95-lb block B. vA=5 ft/s, vB=9 ft/s.","method":"Conservacion de momento - bala multiple impacto","steps":["mAvA + mBvB = (6)(5)+(4.95)(9) = 74.55 lb*ft/s","(a) m = 74.55 / (v0-vB) = 74.55/1491 = 0.0500 lb = 0.800 oz","(b) m*v0 = m*v1 + mA*vA  =>  v1 = (0.05*1500 - 6*5)/0.05 = 900 ft/s"],"final_answer":"(a) m = 0.800 oz  |  (b) v1 = 900 ft/s","page_num":801},"14.7":{"problem_text":"Bumper cars A(240kg), B(260kg), C(235kg). vA=2m/s, vB=0, vC=-1.5m/s. e=0.8.","method":"Conservacion de momento + coeficiente de restitucion","steps":["(a) A y C golpean B simultaneamente:","mAvA + mBvB + mCvC = mAvA + mBvB + mCvC  (3 incognitas)","vB-vA = e(vA-vB) = 0.8(2-0) = 1.6","vC-vB = e(vB-vC) = 0.8(0+1.5) = 1.2","Solucion: vA=-1.288 m/s, vB=0.312 m/s, vC=1.512 m/s","(b) A golpea B primero:","(240)(2) = 240vA+260vB; vB-vA=1.6  =>  vA=0.128, vB=1.728","B golpea C: (260)(1.728)+(235)(-1.5)=260vB+235vC; vC-vB=2.5824","  =>  vB=-1.030, vC=1.552","A golpea B otra vez: vA=-0.956, vB=-0.0296"],"final_answer":"(a) vA=1.288, vB=0.312, vC=1.512 m/s  |  (b) vA=0.956, vB=0.0296, vC=1.552 m/s","page_num":803},"14.9":{"problem_text":"System mA=3kg, mB=4kg, mC=5kg with velocities vA=-4i+4j+6k, vB=-6i+8j+4k, vC=2i-6j-4k.","method":"Momento angular de sistema de particulas - producto vectorial","steps":["Ho = rA x mAvA + rB x mBvB + rC x mCvC","rA=1.2i+1.5k, rB=0.9i+1.2j+1.2k, rC=2.4j+1.8k","Calcular cada producto vectorial (determinante 3x3)","= (-18i-39.6j+14.4k) + (-19.2i-43.2j+57.6k) + (6i+18j-24k)","Ho = -31.2i - 64.8j + 48.0k  kg.m^2/s"],"final_answer":"Ho = -(31.2)i - (64.8)j + (48.0)k  kg.m^2/s","page_num":808},"14.15":{"problem_text":"900-lb space vehicle v=(1200i) ft/s. Explodes into 450lb@A(3840,-960,-1920), 300lb@B(6480,1200,2640), find C at t=4s.","method":"Centro de masa - sin fuerzas externas sigue trayectoria original","steps":["Sin fuerzas externas: rG = vG*t = (1200)(4)i = 4800i ft","m*rG = mA*rA + mB*rB + mC*rC","900(4800i) = 450(3840i-960j-1920k) + 300(6480i+1200j+2640k) + 150*rC","150*rC = 4320000i - 648000j*... => calcular por componentes","rC = 4320i + 480j + 480k  ft"],"final_answer":"rC = (4320 ft)i + (480 ft)j + (480 ft)k","page_num":815},"14.17":{"problem_text":"Airplane 1500kg + helicopter 3000kg collide at 1200m altitude. Find where airplane falls.","method":"Centro de masa en explosion/colision + cinematica del proyectil","steps":["Velocidad del helicoptero antes: vH = 8400m/(4*60s) i = 35 m/s i","Velocidad del avion antes: vA = (16000i-12000j)/(240s) = 66.67i-50j m/s","V_cdm = (mH*vH + mA*vA)/(mH+mA) = (3000*35i + 1500*(66.67i-50j))/4500","V_cdm = 45.556i - 16.667j m/s","Tiempo de caida: t = sqrt(2h/g) = sqrt(2400/9.81) = 15.64 s","rG = V_cdm * t = (712.55i - 260.69j) m","mH*rH1+mH2*rH2+mA*rA = (mH+mA)*rG","=> rA = (1004i - 48.7j) m"],"final_answer":"Avion cae en (1004 m, -48.7 m)","page_num":817},"14.31":{"problem_text":"Energy lost in 14.1 impacts (15-kg suitcase first). Calculate for each impact.","method":"Energia perdida en impacto - T_perdida = T_antes - T_despues","steps":["(a) 1er impacto (15kg hits 25kg carrier):","T_antes = (1/2)(15)(3)^2 = 67.5 J","v1 = 1.125 m/s (del 14.1)","T_despues = (1/2)(40)(1.125)^2 = 25.31 J","Perdida (a) = 67.5 - 25.31 = 42.2 J","(b) 2do impacto (20kg hits 40kg system):","T_antes = 25.31 + (1/2)(20)(2)^2 = 65.31 J","v2 = 1.417 m/s (del 14.1)","T_despues = (1/2)(60)(1.417)^2 = 60.21 J","Perdida (b) = 5.10 J"],"final_answer":"(a) 42.2 J  |  (b) 5.10 J","page_num":836},"14.35":{"problem_text":"Cars mA=1600kg, mB=900kg, vA=90km/h, vB=60km/h head-on. Show EA/EB = mB/mA.","method":"Colision plastica - energia absorbida proporcional a inverso de masa","steps":["CDM velocity: V = (mA*vA + mB*(-vB))/(mA+mB)","vA=25m/s, vB=16.667m/s: V = (1600*25 - 900*16.667)/2500 = 10 m/s","Velocidades relativas al CDM: uA=15 m/s, uB=-26.667 m/s","EA = (1/2)*mA*uA^2 = (1/2)(1600)(15)^2 = 180 kJ","EB = (1/2)*mB*uB^2 = (1/2)(900)(26.667)^2 = 320 kJ","EA/EB = 180/320 = 0.5625 = 900/1600 = mB/mA  QED"],"final_answer":"EA=180 kJ, EB=320 kJ, EA/EB = mB/mA","page_num":842},"14.57":{"problem_text":"Water stream A=500mm2, v=25m/s hits stationary plate. Find force P.","method":"Flujo de fluido - principio impulso-momento","steps":["dm/dt = rho*A*v = 1000 * 500e-6 * 25 = 12.5 kg/s","Impulso-momento: (dm)*v - P*dt = (dm)*0","P = (dm/dt)*v = (12.5)(25) = 312 N"],"final_answer":"P = 312 N","page_num":877},"14.91":{"problem_text":"Space shuttle: 3 engines, each burns 340 kg/s at 3750 m/s relative velocity.","method":"Cohete - empuje = u * dm/dt","steps":["Empuje un motor: P = u*(dm/dt) = (3750)(340) = 1.275e6 N","Total 3 motores: F = 3 * 1.275e6 = 3.825e6 N = 3.83 MN"],"final_answer":"Empuje total = 3.83 MN","page_num":923},"14.94":{"problem_text":"Rocket 1200kg (1000kg fuel), burns 12.5 kg/s, ejected 4000 m/s, vertical launch.","method":"Cohete vertical - a = P/m - g con masa variable","steps":["Empuje: P = u*dm/dt = 4000*12.5 = 50000 N","EcMov: a = P/m - g","(a) inicio m=1200kg: a = 50000/1200 - 9.81 = 31.9 m/s^2","(b) fin combustible m=200kg: a = 50000/200 - 9.81 = 240 m/s^2"],"final_answer":"(a) a = 31.9 m/s^2  |  (b) a = 240 m/s^2","page_num":926}};
